owspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|1999\n| Don't You Turn Your Back On Me\n| Daniel Lwowski\n|-\n| Open Your Eyes\n| Jeannine Panaccione\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|2000\n| Big In Japan\n| Er\u00e7in Filizli\n|-\n| No Speech\n| Jorf Somner\n|-\n| Living In A Lie\n| Er\u00e7in Filizli\n|-\n| I Want It\n| n/a\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|2001\n| Kumba Yo!\n| Norman Hafezi\n|-\n| D\u00f6del Up\n| {{Ill|Gerhard Hahn (director)|de|3=Gerhard Hahn (Regisseur)|lt=Gerhard Hahn}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|2003\n| Pretty In Scarlet\n| rowspan=\"3\" | Joern Heitmann\n|-\n| You Can't Stop Me\n|-\n| Quietly\n|-\n| Sing That Song\n| n/a\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|2004\n| Sugar Skin\n| n/a\n|-\n| Break The Line\n| n/a\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|2011\n| Oh What a Night\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Markus Gerwinat\n|-\n| Sunday Lover\n|-\n| This Time\n| Oliver Sommer\n|-\n|2012\n| When the Ships Arrive\n| Holger Gutt\n|-\n|2014\n| Close to the sun\n| \n|}\n\n==Video albums==\n\n* ''Guano T-Apes'' (VHS, 1998)\n* ''Don't Give Me Names'' (VHS & DVD, 2000)\n* [[Guano Apes \u2013 Live|Live]] (DVD, 2003)\n* [[Planet Of The Apes / The Documentary (DVD)|''Planet Of The Apes / The Documentary'' (DVD)]] (2005)\n* ''Guano Apes \u2013 Live @ Rockpalast'' (2012)\n\n''Guano T-apes'' is a video that documents the development of the Guano Apes from their beginning. With band and individual interviews you get to know the members of the band better and experience curiosities and events from daily life in the music business. Along with the video clips, it contains lots of live material shot during the tours from Nov., 1997 through the summer of 1998. The video was directed by Richard Anjou and edited by Mathias Dohmbrinck.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Guano Apes}}\n\n[[Category:Discographies of German artists]]\n[[Category:Guano Apes|Discography]]\n", "name_user": "Diskografienerd", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStudio albums", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guano_Apes_discography"}
{"title_page": "1967 USS Forrestal fire", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:1967 USS ''Forrestal'' fire}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox news event\n|title = 1967 USS ''Forrestal'' fire\n|image=USS Rupertus (DD-851) stands by to assist the burning USS Forrestal (CVA-59), 29 July 1967 (USN 1124775).jpg\n|image_size=300px\n|caption=USS ''Forrestal'' on fire, the worst US carrier fire since World War II; the destroyer {{USS|Rupertus|DD-851|2}} maneuvers to within {{convert|20|ft|abbr=on|0}} to use fire hoses.\n| map = {{Location map|South China Sea| width = 290px |mark = Gfi-set01-lost-ship.png |label={{USS|Forrestal|CV-59|6}} }}\n|date=29 July 1967\n|time=02:52 UTC (10:52 a.m. Hotel time)\n|place=[[Gulf of Tonkin]], {{coord|19|9|5|N|107|23|5|E}}<ref name=\"DANFS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/f3/forrestal.htm |title=USS ''Forrestal'' (CV-59) |date=2 August 2007 |website=DANFS |publisher=Naval Historical Center |accessdate=18 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080320002709/http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/f3/forrestal.htm |archivedate=20 March 2008 |df= }}</ref>\n|reported deaths=134 dead<ref name=Stewart/>\n|reported missing  =\n|outcome  =  [[John Kingsman Beling|Capt. John K. Beling]] absolved of responsibility; no crew members charged. Ship in dry dock for five months.\n|reported injuries=161 injured<ref name=Stewart/>\n|casualties1 = '''Repair costs''': {{US$|72 million|link=yes}}<ref name=Stewart/>\n|casualties2 = '''Aircraft lost''': seven [[McDonnell Douglas F-4 Phantom II|F-4B Phantom II]]; eleven [[Douglas A-4 Skyhawk|A-4E Skyhawks]]; and three [[North American A-5 Vigilante|RA-5C Vigilantes]]; 40 others damaged\n}}\n[[File:A-7E VA-25 dropping bombs over Vietnam c1970.jpg|thumb|A US Navy [[LTV A-7 Corsair II|A-7 Corsair]] drops a load of [[Mark 83 bomb]]s; the relentless bombing campaign had led to the Navy's stocks of Mark 83 bombs dwindling, and had forced on them the use of World War II surplus ordnance, often in poor condition, to maintain the punishing mission rate.]]\n\nOn 29 July 1967, a fire broke out on board the [[aircraft carrier]] {{USS|Forrestal|CV-59|6}} after an electrical anomaly caused a [[Zuni (rocket)|Zuni rocket]] on a [[McDonnell Douglas F-4 Phantom II|F-4B Phantom]] to fire, striking an external fuel tank of an [[Douglas A-4 Skyhawk|A-4 Skyhawk]]. The flammable jet fuel spilled across the [[flight deck]], ignited, and triggered a chain-reaction of explosions that killed 134 sailors and injured 161. At the time, ''Forrestal'' was engaged in combat operations in the [[Gulf of Tonkin]], during the [[Vietnam War]]. The ship survived, but with damage exceeding [[United States dollar|US$]]72 million, not including the damage to aircraft.<ref name=Stewart>{{cite book |last= Stewart |first= Henry P. |title= The Impact of the USS ''Forrestal''{{'}}s 1967 Fire on United States Navy Shipboard Damage Control |type= Master's thesis |publisher= [[United States Army Command and General Staff College]] |location= Fort Leavenworth, KS |year=2004 |url= http://handle.dtic.mil/100.2/ADA429103 |format= PDF |accessdate=2 September 2008}}</ref><ref name=DCFP>{{cite web|publisher=US Navy Damage control museum |url=http://www.dcfp.navy.mil/mc/museum/FORRESTAL/Forrestal1.htm |title=USS ''Forrestal'' (CVA 59) |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080207074706/http://www.dcfp.navy.mil/mc/museum/FORRESTAL/Forrestal1.htm |archivedate=7 February 2008 }}</ref> Future [[United States Senator]] [[John McCain]] and future four-star admiral and [[Commander, U.S. Pacific Fleet|U.S. Pacific Fleet Commander]] [[Ronald J. Zlatoper]] were among the survivors. Lieutenant Tom Treanore returned to the ship as its commander and retired an admiral.<ref>\"Remarks at USS ''Forrestal'' Forty Year Memorial Tribute\". Farrier Fire Fighting School, Norfolk, Virginia. 27 July 2007 Tom Wimberly, Captain, U. S. Navy (Retired)</ref>\n\nThe disaster prompted the Navy to revise its fire fighting practices. It also modified its weapon handling procedures and installed a deck wash down system on all carriers. The newly established Farrier Fire Fighting School Learning Site in Norfolk, Virginia was named after Chief Gerald W. Farrier, the commander of Damage Control Team 8, who was among the first to die in the fire and explosions.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:USS Forrestal (CVA-59) underway at sea on 31 May 1962 (KN-4507).jpg|thumb|left|Since her commissioning in 1955, ''Forrestal'' spent her service alternating between the North Atlantic and Mediterranean; her departure from Norfolk in June 1967 was her first WESTPAC deployment.]]\n[[File:USS Diamond Head (AE-19) anchored off Naples, Italy, on 20 October 1960 (USN 1050684).jpg|thumb|left|''Forrestal'' rendezvoused with the ammunition ship ''Diamond Head'' on 28 July to receive a load of new ordnance, including 16 Korean War-era AN-M65A1 GP 1,000 lb bombs.]]\n\n=== Arrival in Gulf of Tonkin ===\n\n''Forrestal''  departed its home port in [[Norfolk, Virginia]] in early June 1967. After it completed required inspections for the upcoming West Pacific cruise, it sailed to Brazil for a show of force. It then traveled east around the [[Horn of Africa]] and visited [[Naval Air Station Cubi Point]] in the Philippine Islands before sailing to [[Yankee Station]] in the Gulf of Tonkin on 25 July.\n\nAfter arrival at Yankee Station, aircraft from [[Carrier Air Wing Seventeen|Attack Carrier Air Wing 17]] flew approximately 150 missions against targets in [[North Vietnam]] over four days.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navy.mil/navydata/nav_legacy.asp?id=64 |title=USS ''Forrestal'' CVA-59 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=15 June 2009 |website=US Navy |accessdate=13 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150915110332/http://www.navy.mil/navydata/nav_legacy.asp?id=64 |archive-date=15 September 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Vietnam bombing campaign ===\n\nThe ongoing naval bombing campaign during 1967 originating at Yankee Station represented by far the most intense and sustained air attack operation in the [[U.S. Navy]]'s history.  The demand for [[general-purpose bomb]]s (e.g., \"iron bombs\") greatly exceeded production. The inventory of bombs dwindled throughout 1966 and became critically low by 1967.<ref name=cox/> This was particularly true for the new {{convert|1000|lb|abbr=on|0}} [[Mark 83]], which the Navy favored for its power-to-size ratio. A [[CATOBAR|carrier-launched]] [[Douglas A-4 Skyhawk|A-4 Skyhawk]], the Navy's standard light attack / [[ground attack aircraft]], could carry either a single {{convert|2000|lb|kg|abbr=on|0}} bomb, or two 1,000 lb bombs. This gave it the ability to strike two separate hardened targets in a single [[sortie]], which was more effective in most circumstances.\n\nThe [[U.S. Air Force]]'s primary ground attack aircraft in Vietnam was the much heavier, land-based, [[Republic F-105 Thunderchief|F-105 Thunderchief]]. It could simultaneously carry two {{convert|3000|lb|kg|abbr=on|0}} [[Mark 118 bomb|M118]] bombs and four {{convert|750|lb|kg|abbr=on|0}} [[M117 bomb|M117]] bombs. The Air Force had a large supply of these bombs, and did not rely as heavily on the limited supply of 1,000 lb bombs as did the Navy.{{Citation needed|date = July 2014}}\n[[File:RADM John Beling.jpg|thumb|Captain [[John Kingsman Beling|Beling]] was reluctant to take delivery of the Korean War-era 16 AN-M65A1 bombs from USS ''Diamond Head'' but, faced with the prospect of having to cancel the next day's sorties, accepted them.]]\n\n=== Issues with Zuni rockets===\n\nIn addition to bombs, the ground attack aircraft carried unguided {{convert|5|in|mm|abbr=on|0}} [[Zuni (rocket)|Mk-32 \"Zuni\"]] rockets. These rockets were in wide use although they had a reputation for electrical difficulties and accidental firing.<ref name=\"invespart2\"/> It was common for aircraft to launch with six or more rocket packs, each containing four rockets.<ref name=\"invespart2\"/>\n\n=== Specialized fire-fighting teams ===\n\nBased on lessons learned during Japanese attacks on vessels during World War II, most sailors on board ships after World War II received training in fighting shipboard fires. These lessons were gradually lost and by 1967, the U.S. Navy had reverted to the Japanese model at [[Battle of Midway|Midway]] and relied on specialized, highly trained damage control and fire-fighting teams.<ref name=skyhawk/>\n\nThe damage control team specializing in on-deck firefighting for ''Forrestal'' was Damage Control Team No. 8, led by [[Chief petty officer|Chief]] [[Aviation boatswain's mate|Aviation Boatswain's Mate]] Gerald Farrier. They had been shown films during training of Navy ordnance tests demonstrating how a 1,000 lb bomb could be directly exposed to a jet fuel fire for a full ten minutes and still be extinguished and cooled without an explosive [[Cooking off|cook-off]].<ref name=freeman>{{cite book |last=Freeman |first=Gregory A. |title=Sailors to the End: The Deadly Fire on the USS Forrestal and the Heroes Who Fought It |publisher=HarperCollins |year=2004 |isbn=978-0060936907}}</ref>{{rp|126}} However, these tests were conducted using the new Mark 83 1,000 lb bombs, which featured relatively stable [[Composition H6]] explosive and thicker, heat-resistant cases, compared to their predecessors. Because it is [[insensitive munitions|relatively insensitive]] to heat, shock and electricity, Composition H6 is still used as of {{CURRENTYEAR}} in many types of naval ordnance. It is also designed to [[deflagrate]] instead of [[detonate]] when it reaches its ignition point in a fire, either melting the case and producing no explosion at all, or, at most, a subsonic [[low explosive|low order detonation]] at a fraction of its normal power.<ref name=freeman/>{{rp|85}}\n\n=== Unstable ordnance received ===\n\nOn 28 July, the day before the accident, ''Forrestal'' was resupplied with ordnance by the [[ammunition ship]] {{USS|Diamond Head|AE-19|6}}. The load included sixteen 1,000 lb AN/M65A1 \"fat boy\" bombs (so nicknamed because of their short, rotund shape), which ''Diamond Head'' had picked up from [[Subic Bay Naval Base]] and were intended for the next day's second bombing sortie. Some of the batch of AN-M65A1s ''Forrestal'' received were more than a decade old, having spent a portion of that exposed to the heat and humidity of [[Okinawa]] or [[Guam]],<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=DhhnAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT136#v=onepage&q&f=false |title= Dangerous Games: Faces, Incidents, and Casualties of the Cold War |first1= Scott |last1= Baron |first2= James |last2= Wise, Jr |publisher= Naval Institute Press |year= 2013 |isbn= 978-1612514529 |page= 136 |access-date= 20 July 2015 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160512051957/https://books.google.com/books?id=DhhnAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT136#v=onepage&q&f=false |archive-date= 12 May 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> eventually being improperly stored in open-air [[Quonset hut]]s at a disused [[ammunition dump]] on the periphery of Subic Bay Naval Base. Unlike the thick-cased Mark 83 bombs filled with Composition H6, the AN/M65A1 bombs were thin-skinned and filled with [[Composition B]], an older explosive with greater [[sensitivity (explosives)|shock and heat sensitivity]].<ref name=fear>{{Cite web |url=https://nationalinterest.org/feature/us-navy-aircraft-carriers-greatest-fear-its-not-russia-or-22055 |title=A U.S. Navy Aircraft Carrier's Greatest Fear (And It's Not Russia or China) |access-date=12 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731090904/https://nationalinterest.org/feature/us-navy-aircraft-carriers-greatest-fear-its-not-russia-or-22055 |archive-date=31 July 2018 |url-status=live |date=26 August 2017 }}</ref>\n\nComposition B also had the dangerous tendency to become more powerful (up to 50% by weight) and more sensitive if it was old or improperly stored. ''Forrestal''{{'}}s ordnance handlers had never even seen an AN/M65A1 before, and to their shock, the bombs delivered from ''Diamond Head'' were in terrible condition; coated with \"decades of accumulated rust and grime\" and still in their original packing crates (now moldy and rotten); some were stamped with production dates as early as 1953. Most dangerous of all, several bombs were seen to be leaking liquid [[paraffin wax|paraffin]] [[phlegmatized|phlegmatizing agent]] from their seams, an unmistakable sign that the bomb's explosive filler had degenerated with excessive age, and exposure to heat and moisture.<ref name=freeman/>{{rp|87}}<ref name=navylive>{{cite web |title=The Forrestal Fire |first1=John D. |last1=Burlage |url=http://www.navy.mil/navydata/nav_legacy.asp?id=73 |website=Navy News Service |accessdate=23 July 2018 |language=en |date=28 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723064421/http://www.navy.mil/navydata/nav_legacy.asp?id=73 |archive-date=23 July 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=fear/>\n\nAccording to Lieutenant R. R. \"Rocky\" Pratt, a [[naval aviator]] attached to [[VFA-106|VA-106]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.va106vf62.org/gladiator_website_007.htm |title=Gladiator Helmet |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=Gladiator Reunion Group |accessdate=13 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170421060324/http://www.va106vf62.org/gladiator_website_007.htm |archive-date=21 April 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> the concern felt by ''Forrestal''{{'}}s ordnance handlers was striking, with many afraid to even handle the bombs; one officer wondered out loud if they would survive the shock of a [[aircraft catapult|catapult-assisted launch]] without spontaneously detonating, and others suggested they immediately jettison them.<ref name=freeman/>{{rp|86}} ''Forrestal''{{'}}s ordnance officers reported the situation up the chain of command to the ship's commanding officer, Captain [[John Kingsman Beling|John Beling]], and informed him the bombs were, in their assessment, an imminent danger to the ship and should be immediately jettisoned overboard.<ref name=skyhawk/><ref name=cox/>\n\nFaced with this, but still needing 1,000 lb bombs for the next day's missions, Beling demanded ''Diamond Head'' take the AN-M65A1s back in exchange for new Mark 83s,<ref name=freeman/>{{rp|88}} but was told by ''Diamond Head'' that they had none to give him. The AN-M65A1 bombs had been returned to service specifically because there were not enough Mark 83s to go around. According to one crew member on ''Diamond Head'', when they had arrived at Subic Bay to pick up their load of ordnance for the carriers, the base personnel who had prepared the AN-M65A1 bombs for transfer assumed ''Diamond Head'' had been ordered to dump them at sea on the way back to Yankee Station. When notified that the bombs were actually destined for active service in the carrier fleet, the commanding officer of the naval ordnance detachment at Subic Bay was so shocked that he initially refused the transfer, believing a paperwork mistake had been made. At the risk of delaying ''Diamond Head''{{'}}s departure, he refused to sign the transfer forms until receiving written orders from [[CINCPAC]] on the [[teleprinter]], explicitly absolving his detachment of responsibility for the bombs' terrible condition.<ref name=cox/>\n\n=== Unstable bombs stored on deck ===\n\nWith orders to conduct strike missions over North Vietnam the next day, and with no replacement bombs available, Captain Beling reluctantly concluded that he had no choice but to accept the AN-M65A1 bombs in their current condition.<ref name=skyhawk/><ref name=\"dougherty\">{{cite web |title=Bud Dougherty Collection: Disaster on the USS Forrestal |url=https://arlingtonhistoricalsociety.org/2017/06/bud-dougherty-collection-disaster-on-the-uss-forrestal/ |website=Arlington Historical Society |accessdate=26 July 2018 |date=18 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726072002/https://arlingtonhistoricalsociety.org/2017/06/bud-dougherty-collection-disaster-on-the-uss-forrestal/ |archive-date=26 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"collins\">{{cite web |last1=Collins |first1=Elizabeth M. |title=Fire Aboard Ship |url=http://www.navy.mil/ah_online/ftrStory.asp?id=101670 |website=navy.mil |publisher=All Hands |accessdate=23 July 2018 |language=en |date=27 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723064200/http://www.navy.mil/ah_online/ftrStory.asp?id=101670 |archive-date=23 July 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In one concession to the demands of the ordnance handlers, Beling agreed to store all 16 bombs alone on deck in the \"bomb farm\" area between the starboard rail and the carrier's island until they were loaded for the next day's missions. Standard procedure was to store them in the ship's magazine with the rest of the air wing's ordnance; had they been stored as standard, an accidental detonation could easily have destroyed the ship.<ref name=\"freeman\"/>{{rp|273\u201374}}\n\n==Fire and explosions==\n\nWhile preparing for the second sortie of the day, the aft portion of the flight deck was packed wing-to-wing with twelve A-4E Skyhawk, seven [[McDonnell Douglas F-4 Phantom II|F-4B Phantom II]], and two [[North American A-5 Vigilante|Vigilante]] aircraft. A total of 27 aircraft were on deck, fully loaded with bombs, rockets, ammunition, and fuel. Several tons of bombs were stored on wooden pallets on deck in the bomb farm.<ref name=readiness>{{cite web |title=How the 1967 Fire on USS ''Forrestal'' Improved Future U.S. Navy Damage Control Readiness |url=http://usnhistory.navylive.dodlive.mil/2017/07/28/how-the-1967-fire-on-uss-forrestal-improved-future-u-s-navy-damage-control-readiness/ |website=The Sextant |accessdate=26 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726103731/http://usnhistory.navylive.dodlive.mil/2017/07/28/how-the-1967-fire-on-uss-forrestal-improved-future-u-s-navy-damage-control-readiness/ |archive-date=26 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> An F-4B Phantom II (No. 110, BuNo 153061), flown by Lieutenant Commander James E. Bangert and Lieutenant (JG) Lawrence E. McKay from [[VFA-11|VF-11]],<ref name=\"DANFS\"/> was positioned on the aft starboard corner of the deck, pointing about 45 degrees across the ship.<ref name=\"DANFS\"/> It was armed with LAU-10 underwing rocket pods, each containing four unguided {{convert|5|in|mm|abbr=on|1}} [[Zuni (rocket)|Mk-32 \"Zuni\" rockets]]. The Zuni was protected from launching by a safety pin that was only to be removed prior to launch from the catapult.<ref name=navylive/><ref name=\"invespart2\"/>{{rp|57}}\n\n=== Zuni rocket launched ===\n\nAt about 10:51 (local time) on 29 July, an electrical power surge in Phantom No. 110 occurred during the switch from external to internal power. The electrical surge caused one of the four 5-inch Mk-32 Zuni unguided rockets in a pod on external stores station 2 (port inboard station) to fire.<ref name=cox>{{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Samuel J. |title=H-008-6 USS Forrestal Disaster |url=https://www.history.navy.mil/content/history/nhhc/about-us/leadership/director/directors-corner/h-grams/h-gram-008/h-008-6.html |website=www.history.navy.mil |accessdate=26 July 2018 |date=July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190331190626/https://www.history.navy.mil/content/history/nhhc/about-us/leadership/director/directors-corner/h-grams/h-gram-008/h-008-6.html |archive-date=31 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The rocket was later determined to be missing the rocket safety pin, allowing the rocket to launch.<ref name=navylive/> The rocket flew about {{convert|100|ft}} across the flight deck, likely severing the arm of a crewman, and ruptured a {{convert|400|gal|adj=on}} wing-mounted external fuel tank on a Skyhawk from Attack Squadron 46 ([[VA-46 (U.S. Navy)|VA-46]]) awaiting launch.<ref name=\"DANFS\"/><ref name=usnav_investigation>{{cite web |author=US Navy |url=http://www.jag.navy.mil/library/investigations/USS%20FORRESTAL%20FIRE%2012%20AUG%2069%20PT%201.pdf |title= Fire and explosions aboard USS ''Forrestal'' (CV 59) |date=19 September 1967 |publisher=Judge Advocate General |access-date=23 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228152838/http://www.jag.navy.mil/library/investigations/USS%20FORRESTAL%20FIRE%2012%20AUG%2069%20PT%201.pdf |archive-date=28 December 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"invespart2\"/>{{rp|34, 93}}\n\n[[File:CVA-59 fire aft deck plan.png|thumb|left|A drawing of the stern of ''Forrestal'' showing the spotting of aircraft at the time. Likely source of the Zuni was F-4 No. 110. White's and McCain's aircraft (A-4s No. 405 and 416, respectively) are in the right-hand circle.]]\n\n=== Aircraft struck ===\n[[File:USS Forrestal A-4 Skyhawk burning.png|thumb|In the first moments of the disaster, an A-4 Skyhawk burns immediately after its fuel tank is ruptured by a Zuni rocket.]]\nThe official Navy investigation identified the Skyhawk struck by the Zuni as aircraft No. 405, piloted by Lieutenant Commander Fred D. White.<ref name=Stewart/><ref>{{cite news |first=Mike |last=Cherney |title=Veterans salute sailors killed aboard carrier |url=http://content.hamptonroads.com/story.cfm?story=129305&ran=106811 |location=Hampton Roads |work=The Virginian Pilot |pages= 1, 8 |date=28 July 2007 |access-date=28 July 2007|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070926233824/http://content.hamptonroads.com/story.cfm?story=129305&ran=106811 |archivedate = 26 September 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> Lieutenant Commander [[John McCain]] stated in his 1999 book ''[[Faith of My Fathers]]'' that the missile struck his aircraft, alongside White's A-4 Skyhawk. \"On that Saturday morning in July, as I sat in the cockpit of my A-4 preparing to take off, a rocket hit the fuel tank under my airplane.\"<ref name=popmech>{{cite web |last1=McCain |first1=John |title=The 1967 Aircraft Carrier Fire That Nearly Killed John McCain |url=https://www.popularmechanics.com/military/aviation/a14416145/fire-on-the-flight-deck/ |website=Popular Mechanics |accessdate=27 July 2018 |date=September 1974 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180727085322/https://www.popularmechanics.com/military/aviation/a14416145/fire-on-the-flight-deck/ |archive-date=27 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Later accounts relying on his book also state that the rocket struck his A-4 Skyhawk.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ringle |first1=Ken |title=A Navy Ship's Trial by Fire |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1997/08/02/a-navy-ships-trial-by-fire/676aab23-29ee-4d3e-b18f-e1e8894b05c1/?noredirect=on |website=Washington Post |accessdate=23 July 2018 |date=2 August 1997 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723122506/https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1997/08/02/a-navy-ships-trial-by-fire/676aab23-29ee-4d3e-b18f-e1e8894b05c1/?noredirect=on&utm_term=.d75c77c87a95 |archive-date=23 July 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=thisday>{{cite web |title=Rocket causes deadly fire on aircraft carrier - Jul 29, 1967 - HISTORY.com |url=https://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/rocket-causes-deadly-fire-on-aircraft-carrier |website=HISTORY.com |accessdate=26 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726040954/https://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/rocket-causes-deadly-fire-on-aircraft-carrier |archive-date=26 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Forrestal, Navy's 1st 'supercarrier,' changes hands in one-cent transaction |url=https://www.stripes.com/news/navy/forrestal-navy-s-1st-supercarrier-changes-hands-in-one-cent-transaction-1.248584 |website=Stars and Stripes |accessdate=26 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726073847/https://www.stripes.com/news/navy/forrestal-navy-s-1st-supercarrier-changes-hands-in-one-cent-transaction-1.248584 |archive-date=26 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe Zuni rocket's warhead safety mechanism prevented it from detonating. The rocket broke apart on impact with the external fuel tank.<ref name=\"invespart2\"/>{{rp|34}} The highly flammable [[JP-5]] fuel spread on the deck under White's and McCain's A-4s, ignited by numerous fragments of burning rocket propellant, and causing an instantaneous [[conflagration]]. A sailor standing about 100 feet forward was struck by a fragment of the Zuni or the exploding fuel tank. A fragment also punctured the centerline external fuel tank of A-4 #310, positioned just aft of the jet blast deflector of catapult number 3. The resulting fire was fanned by {{convert|32|knot|adj=on|lk=in}} winds and the exhaust of at least three jets.<ref name=usnav_investigation/><ref name=\"collins\"/> Fire quarters and then [[general quarters]] were sounded at 10:52 and 10:53. Condition ZEBRA was declared at 10:59, requiring all hands to secure the ship for maximum survivability, including closing the fire-proof steel doors that separate the ship's compartments.<ref>{{cite web |title=Material Conditions of Readiness - 14325_341 |url=http://navyadvancement.tpub.com/14325/css/Material-Conditions-Of-Readiness-341.htm |website=navyadvancement.tpub.com |accessdate=26 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817083423/http://navyadvancement.tpub.com/14325/css/Material-Conditions-Of-Readiness-341.htm |archive-date=17 August 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe official report states that one [[Korean War]]-era 1,000 lb AN-M65 bomb fell from an A-4 Skyhawk to the deck;<ref name=usnav_investigation/><ref name=\"browning\">{{cite web |last1=Browning |first1=LCdr. Robert \"Bo\" |title=Personal account of the USS Forrestal fire, July 29, 1967 |url=http://www.safetycenter.navy.mil/MEDIA/approach/theydidwhat/Forrestal.htm |publisher=Navy Safety Center |accessdate=23 July 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040206055916/http://www.safetycenter.navy.mil/MEDIA/approach/theydidwhat/Forrestal.htm |archivedate=6 February 2004}}</ref><ref name=chinfo>{{cite web |title=The Forrestal Fire |url=http://www.chinfo.navy.mil/navpalib/ships/carriers/histories/cv59-forrestal/forrestal-fire.html |accessdate=23 July 2018 |archivedate= 8 February 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060208032244/http://www.chinfo.navy.mil/navpalib/ships/carriers/histories/cv59-forrestal/forrestal-fire.html}}</ref> other reports say two.<ref name=\"dougherty\"/><ref name=skyhawk>{{cite web |title=U.S.S. ''Forrestal'' Fire 1967 {{!}} A-4 Skyhawk Association |url=http://a4skyhawk.info/article-unit/cva59-1967fire |website=a4skyhawk.info |accessdate=26 July 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726071859/http://a4skyhawk.info/article-unit/cva59-1967fire |archive-date=26 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The bomb fell in a pool of burning fuel between White's and McCain's aircraft.\n\n[[Damage Control]] Team No. 8, led by Chief Gerald W. Farrier, were the first responders to any incident on the flight deck. They immediately took action. Farrier, without taking the time to locate and put on protective clothing, immediately attempted to smother the bomb with a [[Purple-K|PKP]] fire extinguisher, attempting to delay the fuel fire from spreading and give the pilots time to escape their aircraft.<ref name=\"navylive\"/> Based on their training, the team believed they had a ten-minute window to extinguish the fire before the bombs casing would melt resulting in a low-order explosion.<ref name=\"heroes\"/>\n\n[[File:USS_Forrestal_fire_1_1967.jpg|thumb|A bomb explodes on the aft deck of ''Forrestal'']]\n\nThe pilots, preparing to launch, were strapped into their aircraft. When the fire started and quickly spread, they immediately attempted to escape their aircraft. McCain, pilot of A-4 Skyhawk side No. 416, next to White's, was among the first to notice the flames, and escaped by scrambling down the nose of his A-4 and jumping off the [[Aerial refueling#Probe-and-drogue|refueling probe]]. Lt. Cmdr. Robert \"Bo\" Browning, in an A-4E Skyhawk on the port side, escaped by crossing the flight deck and ducking under the tails of F-4B Phantoms spotted along the starboard side.<ref name=\"browning\"/> CVW-17 operations officer, Lt. Cmdr. Herbert A. Hope of VA-46, escaped by jumping out of the Skyhawk cockpit and rolling off the flight deck and into the starboard man-overboard net. He went to the hangar deck and took command of a firefighting team.\n\n=== Bombs detonate ===\n\nDespite Farrier's constant effort to cool the bomb that had fallen to the deck, the casing suddenly split open and the explosive began to burn brightly.<ref name=usnav_investigation/> Farrier. recognizing that a lethal cook-off was imminent, shouted for his [[damage controlman|firefighters]] to withdraw, but the bomb detonated\u2014one minute and 36 seconds after the start of the fire.<ref name=freeman/>{{rp|123\u201324}} The unstable Composition B in the old bombs enhanced the power of the explosions.<ref name=skyhawk/> Thirty-five personnel were in close proximity to the blast. Two fire control teams were virtually destroyed; Farrier and all but three of his men were killed instantly. Twenty-seven men were injured.<ref name=usnav_investigation/>\n\n\"I saw a dozen people running... into the fire, just before the bomb cooked off,\" Lt. Cmdr. Browning later said.<ref name=\"browning\"/><ref name=\"heroes\"/> McCain saw another pilot on fire, and turned to help him, when the first bomb detonated. McCain was knocked backwards 10 feet, struck by shrapnel and wounded. White managed to get out of his burning aircraft but was killed by the detonation of the first bomb.<ref name=\"heroes\">{{cite web |title=A Ship Full of Heroes |url=http://www.news.navy.mil:80/media/allhands/acrobat/ah196711.pdf |publisher=All Hands |accessdate=24 July 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040119140044/http://www.news.navy.mil/media/allhands/acrobat/ah196711.pdf |archivedate=19 January 2004 |pages=7\u201311 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Not all of the pilots were able to get out of their aircraft in time. Lt Ken McMillen escaped. LT(JG) Don Dameworth and LT(JG) David Dollarhide were injured escaping their aircraft. Lt. Cmdrs Gerry Stark and Dennis Barton were missing.<ref name=\"heroes\"/>\n\n=== Fire enters lower decks ===\n\nThe first bomb detonation destroyed White's and McCain's aircraft, blew a crater in the [[armored flight deck]], and sprayed the deck and crew with [[Fragmentation (weaponry)|bomb fragments]] and shrapnel from the destroyed aircraft. Burning fuel poured through the hole in the deck into occupied berthing compartments below. In the tightly packed formation on the aft deck, every aircraft, all fully fueled and bomb-laden, was damaged. All seven F-4s caught fire.<ref name=skyhawk/>\n\nLieutenant James J. Campbell recoiled for a few moments in stunned dismay as burning torches tumbled toward him, until their screams stirred him to action.<ref name=DANFS/> Several men jumped or were blown into the ocean. Neighboring ships came alongside and pulled the men from the water.<ref name=\"heroes\"/> When Browning got back on deck, he recalled, \"The port quarter of the flight deck where I was is no longer there.\"<ref name=DANFS/>\n\nTwo more of the unstable 1,000 lb bombs exploded 10 seconds after the first, and a fourth blew up 44 seconds after that. A total of ten bombs exploded during the fire.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pnj.com/story/news/2017/07/29/uss-forrestal-fire-commemoration-reminder-heroism-service-and-sacrifice/521042001/|title=USS Forrestal fire commemoration a reminder of 'heroism, service and sacrifice' |date=29 July 2017 |work=Pensacola News Journal|access-date=2018-10-06|language=en}}</ref> Bodies and debris were hurled as far as the bow of the ship.\n\nIn less than five minutes, seven or eight 1,000-pound bombs,<ref name=skyhawk/><ref name=\"beauregard\"/> one 750-pound bomb, one {{convert|500|lb|adj=on|0}} bomb, and several missile and rocket warheads heated by the fire exploded with varying degrees of violence.<ref name=\"beauregard\">{{cite web |last1=Beauregard |first1=Raymond L |title=The USS Forrestal (CVA-59) fire and munition explosions {{!}} The History of Insensitive Munitions |url=http://www.insensitivemunitions.org/history/the-uss-forrestal-cva-59-fire-and-munition-explosions/ |website=www.insensitivemunitions.org |accessdate=26 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726103548/http://www.insensitivemunitions.org/history/the-uss-forrestal-cva-59-fire-and-munition-explosions/ |archive-date=26 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Several of the explosions of the 1,000-pound Korean War-era AN-M65 Composition B bombs were estimated to be as much as 50% more powerful than a standard 1,000-pound bomb, due to the badly degraded Composition B.<ref name=usnav_investigation/> The ninth explosion was attributed to a [[sympathetic detonation]] between an AN-M65 and a newer 500 lb [[M117 bomb|M117]] H6 bomb that were positioned next to each other. The other H6-based bombs performed as designed and either burned on the deck or were jettisoned, but did not detonate under the heat of the fires.<ref name=skyhawk/> The ongoing detonations prevented fire suppression efforts during the first critical minutes of the disaster.<ref name=usnav_investigation/>\n\nThe explosions tore seven holes in the flight deck. About {{convert|40000|gal}} of burning jet fuel from ruptured aircraft tanks poured across the deck and through the holes in the deck into the aft hangar bay and berthing compartments. The explosions and fire killed fifty night crew personnel who were sleeping in berthing compartments below the aft portion of the flight deck. Forty-one additional crew members were killed in internal compartments in the aft portion of ''Forrestal''.<ref name=skyhawk/><ref name=usnav_investigation/>\n\n[[File:USS_Forrestal_fire_RA-5Cs_burning_1967.jpg|thumb|Two North American RA-5C Vigilante aircraft of heavy reconnaissance squadron RVAH-11 Checkertails are burning on the starboard side aft of the island, while crewmen remove AGM-45 Shrike missiles in the foreground.]]\n\nPersonnel from all over the ship rallied to fight the fires and control further damage. They pushed aircraft, missiles, rockets, bombs, and burning fragments over the side. Sailors manually jettisoned numerous 250 and 500 lb bombs by rolling them along the deck and off the side. Sailors without training in firefighting and damage control took over for the depleted damage control teams. Unknowingly, inexperienced hose teams using seawater washed away the efforts of others attempting to smother the fire with foam.<ref name=\"heroes\"/><ref name=DANFS/>\n\n=== Fires controlled ===\n[[File:USS Forrestal explosion 29 July 1967.jpg|thumb|The initial explosions killed or seriously injured most of the ship's specially trained damage control and firefighting teams, requiring the rest of the crew to step in and combat the subsequent fires.]]\n\nThe destroyer {{USS|George K. MacKenzie|DD-836|6}} pulled men from the water and directed its fire hoses on the burning ship. Another destroyer, {{USS|Rupertus|DD-851|6}}, maneuvered as close as {{convert|20|feet}} to ''Forrestal'' for 90 minutes, directing her own on-board fire hoses at the burning flight and hangar deck on the starboard side, and at the port-side aft 5-inch gun mount.<ref name=\"logs\" /> Rear Admiral and Task Group commander Harvey P. Lanham, aboard ''Forrestal'', called the actions of ''Rupertus'' commanding officer Commander Edwin Burke<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navsource.org/archives/05/851.htm |title=USS ''Rupertus'' (DD-851) |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=navsource.org |accessdate=13 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150821083929/http://www.navsource.org/archives/05/851.htm |archive-date=21 August 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> an \"act of magnificent seamanship\".<ref name=\"logs\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navsource.org/archives/02/cv-59/59f-0729.htm |title=The Forrestal Fire, July 29, 1967 Ship's Logs |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=14 November 2011 |website=navsource.org |accessdate=13 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150724122601/http://www.navsource.org/archives/02/cv-59/59f-0729.htm |archive-date=24 July 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> At 11:47 am, ''Forrestal'' reported the flight deck fire was under control. About 30 minutes later, they had put out the flight deck fires. Fire fighting crews continued to fight fires below deck for many more hours.<ref name=\"logs\" />\n\nUndetonated bombs were continually found during the afternoon. [[Lieutenant (junior grade)|LT(JG)]] Robert Cates, the carrier's explosive ordnance demolition officer, recounted later how he had \"noticed that there was a 500-pound bomb and a 750-pound bomb in the middle of the flight deck... that were still smoking. They hadn't detonated or anything; they were just setting there smoking. So I went up and defused them and had them jettisoned.\" Another sailor volunteered to be lowered by line through a hole in the flight deck to defuse a live bomb that had dropped to the 03 level\u2014even though the compartment was still on fire and full of smoke. Later on, Cates had himself lowered into the compartment to attach a line to the bomb so it could be hauled up to the deck and jettisoned.<ref name=chinfo/>\n\nThroughout the day, the ship's medical staff worked in dangerous conditions to assist their comrades. The number of casualties quickly overwhelmed the ship's medical teams, and ''Forrestal'' was escorted by {{USS|Henry W. Tucker|DD-875|6}} to rendezvous with hospital ship {{USS|Repose|AH-16|6}} at 20:54, allowing the crew to begin transferring the dead and wounded at 22:53.<ref name=DANFS/> Firefighter Milt Crutchley said, \"The worst was going back into the burned-out areas later and finding your dead and wounded shipmates.\" He said it was extremely difficult to remove charred, blackened bodies locked in [[rigor mortis]] \"while maintaining some sort of dignity for your fallen comrades.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ringle |first1=Ken |title=A Navy Ship's Trial by Fire |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1997/08/02/a-navy-ships-trial-by-fire/676aab23-29ee-4d3e-b18f-e1e8894b05c1/?noredirect=on |website=Washington Post |accessdate=25 July 2018 |date=2 August 1997 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180725054947/https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1997/08/02/a-navy-ships-trial-by-fire/676aab23-29ee-4d3e-b18f-e1e8894b05c1/?noredirect=on&utm_term=.4836e6836cb2 |archive-date=25 July 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAt 5:05, a [[Muster (military)|muster]] of ''Forrestal'' crewmen\u2014both in the carrier and aboard other ships\u2014was begun. It took many hours to account for the ship's crew. Wounded and dead had been transferred to other ships, and some men were missing, either burned beyond recognition or blown overboard.  At 6:44&nbsp;pm, fires were still burning in the ship's carpenter shop and in the aft compartments. At 8:33 pm, the fires in the 02 and 03 levels were contained, but the areas were still too hot to enter. Fire fighting was greatly hampered because of smoke and heat. Crew members cut additional holes in the flight deck to help fight fires in the compartments below. At 12:20&nbsp;am, July 30, 14 hours after the fires had begun, all the fires were controlled. ''Forrestal'' crew members continued to put out hot spots, clear smoke, and cool hot steel on the 02 and 03 levels. The fires were declared out at 4:00 am.<ref name=chinfo/><ref name=DANFS/>\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[File:USS Forrestal about one month after 1967 fire.jpg|thumb|''Forrestal'' put into Cubi Point in the Philippines to be patched before returning to the United States, where she was drydocked for eight months of repairs.]]\n\nThe fire left 134 men dead<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.manchestertimes.com/?p=3792 | title=Forty-five years later, veteran remembers worst naval disaster since WW II | work=Manchester Times| date=24 July 2012 | accessdate=12 April 2015 | author=Coffelt, John | quote=Before the sun came up that Saturday morning, Seaman Kenneth Dyke fell into the warm waters 60 miles off the Gulf of Tonkin where the ship was taking part in operations at Yankee Station, according to the online records of the ship's log. | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518103515/http://www.manchestertimes.com/?p=3792 | archive-date=18 May 2015 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> and 161 more injured.<ref name=Stewart/> It was the worst loss of life on a U.S. Navy ship since World War II.<ref name=thisday/> Of the 73 aircraft aboard the carrier, 21 were destroyed and 40 were damaged.<ref name=navymil>{{cite web |title=The Catastrophic Fire on Board USS ''Forrestal'' |url=https://www.history.navy.mil/browse-by-topic/disasters-and-phenomena/forrestal-fire.html |website=www.history.navy.mil |accessdate=25 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170713233406/https://www.history.navy.mil/browse-by-topic/disasters-and-phenomena/forrestal-fire.html |archive-date=13 July 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nTwenty-one aircraft were stricken from naval inventory: seven F-4B Phantom IIs, eleven A-4E Skyhawks, and three [[North American A-5 Vigilante|RA-5C Vigilantes]].<ref name=\"DANFS\"/>\n\nThe ship's chaplains held a memorial service in Hangar Bay One for the crewmen which was attended by more than 2,000 of ''Forrestal's'' crew.\n\n=== Temporary repairs ===\n[[File:Forrestal limping home '67.JPG|thumb|Damage sustained to ''Forrestal'']]\nOn 31 July, ''Forrestal'' arrived at [[Naval Air Station Cubi Point]] in the Philippines, to undertake repairs sufficient to allow the ship to return to the United States. During welcoming ceremonies, a fire alarm signal alerted crews to a fire in mattresses within the burned-out compartments.<ref name=popmech/>\n\n=== Investigation begun ===\n\nA special group, the Aircraft Carrier Safety Review Panel, was convened on 15 August in the Philippines. Owing to the necessity of returning the ship to the United States for repair, the panel acted quickly to interview personnel on board the ship.<ref name=tragic/>\n\n===Ordnance issues found ===\n[[File:USS Forrestal (CV-59) cost of the fire.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Sailors carefully lower the first of their shipmates killed in the fire to the Leyte Pier at [[Naval Air Station Cubi Point]] in the Philippines.]]\n\nInvestigators identified issues with [[stray voltage]] in the circuitry of the LAU-10 rocket launchers and Zuni missiles. They also identified issues with the aging 1,000 lb \"fat bombs\" carried for the strike, which were discovered to have dated from the Korean War in 1953.<ref name=DANFS/>\n\n=== Safety procedures overridden ===\n\nThe board of investigation stated, \"Poor and outdated doctrinal and technical documentation of ordnance and aircraft equipment and procedures, evident at all levels of command, was a contributing cause of the accidental rocket firing.\" However, the doctrine and procedures employed were not unique to ''Forrestal''. Other carriers had problems with the Zuni rockets.<ref name=cox/>\n\nThe investigation found that safety regulations should have prevented the Zuni rocket from firing. A triple ejector rack (TER) electrical safety pin was designed to prevent any electrical signal from reaching the rockets before the aircraft was launched, but it was also known that high winds could sometimes catch the attached tags and blow them free. In addition to the pin, a \"pigtail\" connected the electrical wiring of the missile to the rocket pod. US Navy regulations required the pigtail be connected only when the aircraft was attached to the catapult and ready to launch, but the ordnance officers found this slowed down the launch rate.<ref name=\"invespart2\"/>{{rp|57}}\n\nThe Navy investigation found that four weeks before the fire, ''Forrestal''{{'}}s Weapons Coordination Board, along with members of the Weapons Planning Board, held a meeting to discuss the issue of attaching the pigtail at the catapult. Launches were sometimes delayed when a crew member had difficulty completing the connection. They agreed on a deviation from standard procedure. In a memorandum of the meeting, they agreed to \"Allow ordnance personnel to connect pigtails 'in the pack', prior to taxi, leaving only safety pin removal at the cat.\" The memo, written on 8 July 1967, was circulated to the ship's operations officer. But the memo and the decision were never communicated to Captain Beling, the ship's commanding officer, who was required to approve such decisions.<ref name=\"invespart3\">{{cite web |title=Fire and Explosion aboard USS ''Forrestal'' (CVA-59) Part 2 |url=http://www.jag.navy.mil/library/investigations/USS%20FORRESTAL%20FIRE%2012%20AUG%2069%20PT%202.pdf |accessdate=26 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170109101458/http://www.jag.navy.mil/library/investigations/USS%20FORRESTAL%20FIRE%2012%20AUG%2069%20PT%202.pdf |archive-date=9 January 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{rp|65}}\n\n=== Causes identified ===\n\nThe official inquiry found that the ordnance crew acted immediately on the Weapons Coordination Board's decision. They found that the pigtail was connected early, that the TER pin on the faulty Zuni missile was likely blown free, and that the missile fired when a power surge occurred as the pilot transferred his systems from external to internal power.<ref name=navylive/><ref name=\"invespart2\"/>{{rp|57}} Their report concluded that a ZUNI rocket on the portside TER-7 on external stores station 2 of F-4B No. 110 of VF-11, spotted on the extreme starboard quarter of the flight deck, struck A-4 No. 405, piloted by Lt. Cmdr. Fred D. White, on the port side of the aft deck. The accidental firing was due to the simultaneous malfunction of three components: CA42282 pylon electrical disconnect, TER-7 safety switch, and LAU-10/A shorting device. They concluded that the CA42282 pylon electrical disconnect had a design defect, and found that the TER-7 safety pin was poorly designed, making it easy to confuse with ordnance pins used in the AERO-7 Sparrow Launcher, which if used by mistake would not operate effectively.<ref name=\"invespart2\">{{cite web|title=Official investigation Part 3|url=http://www.jag.navy.mil/library/investigations/USS%20FORRESTAL%20FIRE%2012%20AUG%2069%20PT%203.pdf|publisher=Judge Advocate General|accessdate=27 August 2018|date=19 September 1967|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920103030/http://www.jag.navy.mil/library/investigations/USS%20FORRESTAL%20FIRE%2012%20AUG%2069%20PT%203.pdf|archive-date=20 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Drydock repairs ===\n\nWhen temporary repairs in the Philippines were completed, ''Forrestal'' departed on 11 August, arriving at [[Naval Station Mayport]] in Florida on 12 September to disembark the remaining aircraft and air group personnel stationed in Florida. Two days later, ''Forrestal'' returned to Norfolk to be welcomed home by over 3,000 family members and friends of the crew, gathered on Pier 12 and onboard {{USS|Randolph|CV-15|2}}, ''Forrestal''{{'}}s host ship.<ref name=DANFS/>\n[[File:Forrestal fire 40th Anniversary memorial ceremony flags and photos.jpg|thumb|left|Flags and photos displayed at a 40th anniversary memorial ceremony in Norfolk, Virginia.]]\n\nFrom 19 September 1967 to 8 April 1968, ''Forrestal'' underwent repairs in [[Norfolk Naval Shipyard]], beginning with removal of the starboard deck-edge elevator, which was stuck in place. It had to be cut from the ship while being supported by the shipyard's [[Crane (machine)#Hammerhead|hammerhead crane]]. The carrier occupied [[drydock]] number 8 from 21 September 1967, until 10 February 1968, displacing {{USS|John King|DDG-3|6}}, an oil tanker, and a minesweeper that were occupying the drydock. During the post-fire refit, {{convert|175 |feet}} of the flight deck was replaced, along with about 200 compartments on the 03, 02, 01 decks. The ship's four aft [[5\"/54 caliber Mark 42 gun]]s were removed. The forward four guns had been removed prior to 1962. The repair cost about $72 million (equal to more than $602 million in 2019 dollars), and took nearly five months to complete.<ref>{{cite web |title=The USS ''Forrestal'' (CVA-59) fire and munition explosions {{!}} The History of Insensitive Munitions |url=http://www.insensitivemunitions.org/history/the-uss-forrestal-cva-59-fire-and-munition-explosions/ |website=www.insensitivemunitions.org |accessdate=13 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726103548/http://www.insensitivemunitions.org/history/the-uss-forrestal-cva-59-fire-and-munition-explosions/ |archive-date=26 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=readiness/><ref>{{cite web |title=Aircraft Carrier Photo Index: USS ''Forrestal'' (CVA-59) |url=http://www.navsource.org/archives/02/cv-59/59f-09.htm |website=www.navsource.org |accessdate=26 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726234122/http://www.navsource.org/archives/02/cv-59/59f-09.htm |archive-date=26 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Beling reassigned ===\n\n[[John Kingsman Beling|Captain Beling]], as an Admiral-selectee, received orders to report to Washington, D.C., as the Director of Development Programs in Naval Operations, reporting to Chief of Naval Operations Admiral [[Thomas H. Moorer]]. On 18 September 1967, Captain Robert B. Baldwin assumed command of ''Forrestal''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Aircraft Carrier Photo Index: USS ''Forrestal'' (CVA-59) |url=http://www.navsource.org/archives/02/cv-59/59f-09.htm |website=www.navsource.org |accessdate=31 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726234122/http://www.navsource.org/archives/02/cv-59/59f-09.htm |archive-date=26 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> From 8 to 15 April 1968, he sailed the ship down the [[Elizabeth River (Virginia)|Elizabeth River]] and out into the waters off the [[Virginia Capes]] for post-repair trials, the ship's first time at sea in 207 days. While accomplishing trials, the ship also recorded its first arrested landing since the fire, when Commander Robert E. Ferguson, Commander, CVW-17, landed on board.<ref name=DANFS/>\n\n=== Beling absolved of responsibility ===\n\nThe Naval investigation panel's findings were released on 18 October. They concluded Beling knew that the Zuni missiles had a history of problems, and he should have made more effort to confirm that the ordnance crew was following procedure in handling the ordnance.<ref name=\"invespart2\"/> They ruled he was not responsible for the disaster, but he was nonetheless transferred to staff work, and never returned to active command.\n\nBeling was assigned temporary duty on the staff of Admiral [[Ephraim P. Holmes]], Commander-in-Chief of the U.S. Atlantic Fleet. Holmes disagreed with many portions of the Navy's report into the ''Forrestal'' disaster, including the section clearing Beling. He had Beling assigned to his staff so he could issue a letter of reprimand. By holding Beling responsible he would effectively end his career. Holmes attached the reprimand to the final report, but when Admiral Moorer endorsed the report, he ordered Admiral Holmes to rescind and remove the reprimand.<ref name=\"freeman\" /><ref name=skyhawk/>\n\nThe investigation panel recommended several changes to safety procedures aboard carriers. This included development of a remote-control fire-fighting system for the flight deck, development of more stable ordnance, improvement in survival equipment, and increased training in fire survival.<ref name=tragic>{{cite web |title=The Tragic Fire July 29, 1967 |url=http://forrestal.org:80/fidfacts/page14.htm |website=forrestal.org |accessdate=6 August 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060221012853/http://forrestal.org/fidfacts/page14.htm |archivedate=21 February 2006 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The U.S. Navy implemented safety reviews for weapons systems brought on board ships for use or for transshipment. This evaluation is still carried out by the [[Weapon System Safety|Weapon System Explosives Safety Review Board]].<ref name=cox/><ref name=freeman/>{{rp|123,124}} The fire aboard ''Forrestal'' was the second of three serious fires to strike American carriers in the 1960s.  A [[USS Oriskany fire|1966 fire]] aboard {{USS|Oriskany|CV-34|6}} killed 44 and injured 138 and a [[USS Enterprise fire|1969 fire]] aboard {{USS|Enterprise|CVN-65|6}} killed 28 and injured 314. The greatest loss of life on a U.S. Navy ship since World War II was when the destroyer {{USS|Hobson|DD-464|6}} collided with the aircraft carrier {{USS|Wasp|CV-18|6}} on 26 April 1952, breaking in half, killing 176.\n\n==Incorrect NASA report==\nA 1995 report, NASA Reference Publication 1374, incorrectly described the ''Forrestal'' fire as a result of [[electromagnetic interference]]. It states, \"a Navy jet landing on the aircraft carrier ''U.S.S. Forrestal'' experienced the uncommanded release of munitions that struck a fully armed and fueled fighter on deck... This accident was caused by the landing aircraft being illuminated by carrier based radar, and the resulting EMI sent an unwanted signal to the weapons system.\"<ref name=\"NASA 1374\">{{cite web |url=https://see.msfc.nasa.gov/sites/see.msfc.nasa.gov/files/rp-1374.pdf |title=Electronic Systems Failures and Anomalies Attributed to Electromagnetic Interference |first=R.D. |last=Leach |editor-first=M.B. |editor-last=Alexander |publisher=Marshall Space Flight Center |date=July 1995 |access-date=21 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161203053322/https://see.msfc.nasa.gov/sites/see.msfc.nasa.gov/files/rp-1374.pdf |archive-date=3 December 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{rp|7}}\n\nThis incorrect description has been cited as a [[cautionary tale]] on the importance of avoiding electromagnetic interference.<ref>David H. Harland and Ralph D. Lorenz, ''Space System Failures'', p. 240, {{ISBN|0-387-21519-0}}, Springer-Praxis, 2005</ref><ref>William Pentland, [https://www.forbes.com/sites/williampentland/2012/09/10/yes-our-gadgets-really-threaten-planes/#5288734b3599 ''Yes, Our Gadgets Really Threaten Planes''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122073059/https://www.forbes.com/sites/williampentland/2012/09/10/yes-our-gadgets-really-threaten-planes/#5288734b3599 |date=22 January 2018 }}, Forbes, 10 September 2012</ref> The report itself lacks an accurate reference to the fire. While text contains a superscript pointing to item 12 in the references section, item 12 in the reference section is to \"Von Achen, W.: ''The Apache Helicopter: An EMI Case History.'' Compliance Engineering, Fall, 1991.\"<ref name=\"NASA 1374\"/>{{rp|19}}\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:US Navy 060215-N-5330L-600 Machinist's Mate 1st Class Timothy B. Golden, looks on as his students apply newly learned skill sets in a training simulator.jpg|thumb|Machinist's Mate 1st Class Timothy B. Golden at Farrier Firefighting School, Naval Station Norfolk, observes students test their fire fighting skills in a training simulator in the basic shipboard firefighting course.]]\n\nEighteen crewmen were buried at [[Arlington National Cemetery]].<ref>{{cite web |publisher= Unofficial Arlington National Cemetery website |url= http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/ussforr.htm |title= USS Forrestal |access-date= 6 February 2008 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080503023538/http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/ussforr.htm |archive-date= 3 May 2008 |url-status=live |df= dmy-all }}</ref> Names of the dead are also listed on the [[Vietnam Veterans Memorial]].\n\nOn 29 July 2017, the USS Forrestal Association commemorated the 50th anniversary of the incident. Members of the military, survivors of the disaster, and family members gathered to memorialize those lost in this incident. Active duty personnel presented American flags to represent each sailor who died.<ref name=fifty/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Software |first1=Web Easy Professional Avanquest |title=50 Year Anniversary USS FORESTALL Fire Memorial Ceremony in Washington D.C. |url=http://www.va106vf62.org/gladiator_website_010.htm |website=www.va106vf62.org |publisher=USS FORRESTAL CVA 59 |accessdate=26 July 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726071943/http://www.va106vf62.org/gladiator_website_010.htm |archive-date=26 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe non-profit USS Forrestal Association was formed in 1990 to preserve the memory of those lost in the tragedy.<ref name=fifty>{{cite web |title=USS Forrestal Tragedy Remembered 50 Years Later |url=https://www.dvidshub.net/news/243170/uss-forrestal-tragedy-remembered-50-years-later |website=DVIDS |accessdate=25 July 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731203727/https://www.dvidshub.net/news/243170/uss-forrestal-tragedy-remembered-50-years-later |archive-date=31 July 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Farrier Fire Fighting School established===\nThe Farrier Fire Fighting School Learning Site in Norfolk, Virginia is named after Chief Gerald W. Farrier, the commander of Damage Control Team 8, who was killed in the initial explosion.<ref name=\"navylive\"/> The school hosts an annual memorial remembering the sailors who lost their lives aboard the ''Forrestal''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jackson |first1=MC3 Shane A. |title=USS Forrestal's fallen remembered at Farrier School ceremony |url=https://www.militarynews.com/norfolk-navy-flagship/oceana/news/uss-forrestal-s-fallen-remembered-at-farrier-school-ceremony/article_737f5129-f862-56a5-87a7-e56c1dafc0f4.html |website=Military News |accessdate=2 August 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180802223547/https://www.militarynews.com/norfolk-navy-flagship/oceana/news/uss-forrestal-s-fallen-remembered-at-farrier-school-ceremony/article_737f5129-f862-56a5-87a7-e56c1dafc0f4.html |archive-date=2 August 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Lessons learned===\n[[File:CVA-42 deck edge water system NAN11-69.jpg|thumb|26 May 1969, the first deck-edge spray system installed on {{USS|Franklin D. Roosevelt|CV-42|2}} as a direct result of the ''Forrestal'' fire.]]\n\nThe fire revealed that ''Forrestal'' lacked a heavy-duty, armored forklift needed to jettison aircraft, particularly heavier planes like the RA-5C Vigilante, as well as heavy or damaged ordnance.<ref name=DANFS/>\n\nThe United States Navy uses the ''Forrestal'' fire and the lessons learned from it when teaching [[damage control]] and ammunition safety. The flight-deck film of the flight operations, titled \"''Learn or Burn''\", became mandatory viewing for firefighting trainees.<ref name=DANFS/> All new Navy recruits are required to view a training video titled ''Trial by Fire: A Carrier Fights for Life'',<ref name=\"trialbyfire\">{{cite web |title= Trial by Fire: A Carrier Fights for Life |url= https://archive.org/details/gov.ntis.ava19833vnb1 |publisher= NTIS |accessdate= 15 September 2011 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110511114912/http://www.archive.org/details/gov.ntis.ava19833vnb1 |archive-date= 11 May 2011 |url-status=live |year= 1973 }}</ref><ref name=\"navylive\"/><ref name=chinfo/> produced from footage of the fire and damage control efforts, both successful and unsuccessful.\n\nFootage revealed that damage-control teams spraying [[firefighting foam]] on the deck to smother the burning fuel, which was the correct procedure, had their efforts negated by crewmen on the other side of the deck spraying seawater, which washed the foam away. The sea water worsened the situation by washing burning fuel through the holes in the flight deck and into the decks below. In response, a \"wash down\" system, which floods the flight deck with foam or water, was incorporated into all carriers, with the first being installed aboard {{USS|Franklin D. Roosevelt|CV-42|2}} during her 1968\u20131969 refit.<ref name=cox/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://ussfranklindroosevelt.com/?page_id=2264 |title=History |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=USS Franklin D. Roosevelt |accessdate=13 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151004200931/http://ussfranklindroosevelt.com/?page_id=2264 |archive-date=4 October 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Many other [[fire prevention|fire-safety]] improvements also stemmed from this incident.<ref name=cox/>\n\nDue to the first bomb blast, which killed nearly all of the trained [[damage controlman|firefighters]] on the ship, the remaining crew, who had no formal firefighting training, were forced to improvise.<ref>{{Cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=chuiyXQKw3I|title=USS Forrestal Mishap July 29, 1967|date=25 November 2006|access-date=26 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161110023541/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=chuiyXQKw3I|archive-date=10 November 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> All current Navy recruits receive week-long training in compartment identification, fixed and portable extinguishers, battle dress, self-contained breathing apparatus and emergency escape breathing devices. Recruits are tested on their knowledge and skills by having to use portable extinguishers and charged hoses to fight fires, as well as demonstrating the ability to egress from compartments that are heated and filled with smoke.<ref name=navylive/>\n\n=== Media ===\n\nThe disaster was a major news story and was featured under the headline \"Inferno at Sea\" on the cover of the 11 August 1967, issue of ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'' magazine.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/politics/azdc/2017/07/29/john-mccain-50-years-ago-uss-forrestal-tragedy/522101001/ |title=Sen. John McCain barely escaped death 50 years ago in the USS Forrestal disaster |last=Nowicki |first=Dan |date=28 July 2017 |work=[[The Arizona Republic]] |access-date=2018-07-27 |language=en |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe incident was featured on the first episode of [[the History Channel]]'s ''[[Shockwave (TV series)|Shockwave]]''<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.history.com/shows/shockwave/season-1/episode-1 |title=Watch Shockwave #1 Full Episode - Shockwave |website=HISTORY |language=en |access-date=2018-07-27 |df=dmy-all |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180727212150/https://www.history.com/shows/shockwave/season-1/episode-1 |archive-date=27 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and the third episode of the second season of the [[National Geographic (TV network)|National Geographic Channel]]'s ''[[Seconds From Disaster]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n''This article contains content in the public domain originally published by the U.S. government.''\n\n==External links==\n\n{{commons category|1967 USS Forrestal fire}}\n* US Navy [http://www.jag.navy.mil/library/investigations/USS%20FORRESTAL%20FIRE%2012%20AUG%2069%20PT%201.pdf Inves - Fire and explosions aboard USS Forrestal (CV 59) Part 1] [http://www.jag.navy.mil/library/investigations/USS%20FORRESTAL%20FIRE%2012%20AUG%2069%20PT%202.pdf Part 2] [http://www.jag.navy.mil/library/investigations/USS%20FORRESTAL%20FIRE%2012%20AUG%2069%20PT%203.pdf Part 3] (Official investigation) 19 Sep 1967 Judge Advocate General\n* US Navy. [http://www.navy.mil/navydata/navy_legacy_hr.asp?id=73 ''Forrestal'' fire]. from ''Naval Aviation News'', October 1967.\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090420103551/http://www.safetycenter.navy.mil/MEDIA/approach/theydidwhat/Forrestal.htm |date=20 April 2009 |title=Personal account of the USS ''Forrestal'' fire, July 29, 1967 }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160304185813/http://www.virtualwall.org/units/forrestal.htm Virtual Wall: A Memorial to the men who died in the ''Forrestal'' fire]\n* US Navy. [http://www.navy.mil/search/display.asp?story_id=2967 Witness to History: USS ''Forrestal'' Fire]. 1 August 2002.\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041105120949/https://wrc.navair-rdte.navy.mil/warfighter_enc/History/dyk/1stpage/forrfire.htm |date=5 November 2004 |title=Did You Know: The terrible fire aboard the USS ''Forrestal'' was the worst single Naval casualty event of the Viet Nam War? }}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.dcfp.navy.mil/mc/museum/FORRESTAL/Forrestal1.htm |title=US Navy Damage Control Museum: USS ''Forrestal'' |accessdate=7 February 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091006020626/http://www.dcfp.navy.mil/mc/museum/FORRESTAL/Forrestal1.htm |archivedate=6 October 2009}} \n* [http://www.navsource.org/archives/02/cv-59/59f-0729.htm NavSource.org: The ''Forrestal'' Fire, 29 July 1967, Ship's Logs]\n;Video\n* {{YouTube|chuiyXQKw3I|Video of USS ''Forrestal'' Mishap 29 July 1967}}\n* [https://archive.org/details/gov.ntis.ava19833vnb1 Trial by Fire: A Carrier Fights for Life] (US Navy Training film via Internet Archive)\n\n{{1967 shipwrecks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:USS Forrestal fire, 1967}}\n[[Category:Industrial fires and explosions in the United States]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1967]]\n[[Category:Non-combat naval accidents]]\n[[Category:Ship fires]]\n[[Category:Filmed accidental deaths|USS Forrestal fire, 1967]]\n[[Category:1967 fires|USS Forrestal fire, 1967]]\n[[Category:1967 disasters in the United States|USS Forrestal fire, 1967]]\n[[Category:1967 in Vietnam]]\n[[Category:July 1967 events]]\n[[Category:Explosions in 1967]]\n[[Category:Gulf of Tonkin]]\n[[Category:Maritime disasters]]\n[[Category:Aircraft carrier fires]]\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:1967 USS ''Forrestal'' fire}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox news event\n|title = 1967 USS ''Forrestal'' fire\n|image=USS Rupertus (DD-851) stands by to assist the burning USS Forrestal (CVA-59), 29 July 1967 (USN 1124775).jpg\n|image_size=300px\n|caption=USS ''Forrestal'' on fire, the worst US carrier fire since World War II; the destroyer {{USS|Rupertus|DD-851|2}} maneuvers to within {{convert|20|ft|abbr=on|0}} to use fire hoses.\n| map = {{Location map|South China Sea| width = 290px |mark = Gfi-set01-lost-ship.png |label={{USS|Forrestal|CV-59|6}} }}\n|date=29 July 1967\n|time=02:52 UTC (10:52 a.m. Hotel time)\n|place=[[Gulf of Tonkin]], {{coord|19|9|5|N|107|23|5|E}}<ref name=\"DANFS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/f3/forrestal.htm |title=USS ''Forrestal'' (CV-59) |date=2 August 2007 |website=DANFS |publisher=Naval Historical Center |accessdate=18 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080320002709/http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/f3/forrestal.htm |archivedate=20 March 2008 |df= }}</ref>\n|reported deaths=134 dead<ref name=Stewart/>\n|reported missing  =\n|outcome  =  [[John Kingsman Beling|Capt. John K. Beling]] absolved of responsibility; no crew members charged. Ship in dry dock for five months.\n|reported injuries=161 injured<ref name=Stewart/>\n|casualties1 = '''Repair costs''': {{US$|72 million|link=yes}}<ref name=Stewart/>\n|casualties2 = '''Aircraft lost''': seven [[McDonnell Douglas F-4 Phantom II|F-4B Phantom II]]; eleven [[Douglas A-4 Skyhawk|A-4E Skyhawks]]; and three [[North American A-5 Vigilante|RA-5C Vigilantes]]; 40 others damaged\n}}\n[[File:A-7E VA-25 dropping bombs over Vietnam c1970.jpg|thumb|A US Navy [[LTV A-7 Corsair II|A-7 Corsair]] drops a load of [[Mark 83 bomb]]s; the relentless bombing campaign had led to the Navy's stocks of Mark 83 bombs dwindling, and had forced on them the use of World War II surplus ordnance, often in poor condition, to maintain the punishing mission rate.]]\n\nOn 29 July 1967, a fire broke out on board the [[aircraft carrier]] {{USS|Forrestal|CV-59|6}} after an electrical anomaly caused a [[Zuni (rocket)|Zuni rocket]] on a [[McDonnell Douglas F-4 Phantom II|F-4B Phantom]] to fire, striking an external fuel tank of an [[Douglas A-4 Skyhawk|A-4 Skyhawk]]. The flammable jet fuel spilled across the [[flight deck]], ignited, and triggered a chain-reaction of explosions that killed 134 sailors and injured 161. At the time, ''Forrestal'' was engaged in combat operations in the [[Gulf of Tonkin]], during the [[Vietnam War]]. The ship survived, but with damage exceeding [[United States dollar|US$]]72 million, not including the damage to aircraft.<ref name=Stewart>{{cite book |last= Stewart |first= Henry P. |title= The Impact of the USS ''Forrestal''{{'}}s 1967 Fire on United States Navy Shipboard Damage Control |type= Master's thesis |publisher= [[United States Army Command and General Staff College]] |location= Fort Leavenworth, KS |year=2004 |url= http://handle.dtic.mil/100.2/ADA429103 |format= PDF |accessdate=2 September 2008}}</ref><ref name=DCFP>{{cite web|publisher=US Navy Damage control museum |url=http://www.dcfp.navy.mil/mc/museum/FORRESTAL/Forrestal1.htm |title=USS ''Forrestal'' (CVA 59) |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080207074706/http://www.dcfp.navy.mil/mc/museum/FORRESTAL/Forrestal1.htm |archivedate=7 February 2008 }}</ref> Future [[United States Senator]] [[John McCain]] and future four-star admiral and [[Commander, U.S. Pacific Fleet|U.S. Pacific Fleet Commander]] [[Ronald J. Zlatoper]] were among the survivors. Lieutenant Tom Treanore returned to the ship as its commander and retired an admiral.<ref>\"Remarks at USS ''Forrestal'' Forty Year Memorial Tribute\". Farrier Fire Fighting School, Norfolk, Virginia. 27 July 2007 Tom Wimberly, Captain, U. S. Navy (Retired)</ref>\n\nThe disaster prompted the Navy to revise its fire fighting practices. It also modified its weapon handling procedures and installed a deck wash down system on all carriers. The newly established Farrier Fire Fighting School Learning Site in Norfolk, Virginia was named after Chief Gerald W. Farrier, the commander of Damage Control Team 8, who was among the first to die in the fire and explosions.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:USS Forrestal (CVA-59) underway at sea on 31 May 1962 (KN-4507).jpg|thumb|left|Since her commissioning in 1955, ''Forrestal'' spent her service alternating between the North Atlantic and Mediterranean; her departure from Norfolk in June 1967 was her first WESTPAC deployment.]]\n[[File:USS Diamond Head (AE-19) underway at sea.jpg|thumb|left|''Forrestal'' rendezvoused with the ammunition ship ''Diamond Head'' on 28 July to receive a load of new ordnance, including 16 Korean War-era AN-M65A1 GP 1,000 lb bombs.]]\n\n=== Arrival in Gulf of Tonkin ===\n\n''Forrestal''  departed its home port in [[Norfolk, Virginia]] in early June 1967. After it completed required inspections for the upcoming West Pacific cruise, it sailed to Brazil for a show of force. It then traveled east around the [[Horn of Africa]] and visited [[Naval Air Station Cubi Point]] in the Philippine Islands before sailing to [[Yankee Station]] in the Gulf of Tonkin on 25 July.\n\nAfter arrival at Yankee Station, aircraft from [[Carrier Air Wing Seventeen|Attack Carrier Air Wing 17]] flew approximately 150 missions against targets in [[North Vietnam]] over four days.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navy.mil/navydata/nav_legacy.asp?id=64 |title=USS ''Forrestal'' CVA-59 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=15 June 2009 |website=US Navy |accessdate=13 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150915110332/http://www.navy.mil/navydata/nav_legacy.asp?id=64 |archive-date=15 September 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Vietnam bombing campaign ===\n\nThe ongoing naval bombing campaign during 1967 originating at Yankee Station represented by far the most intense and sustained air attack operation in the [[U.S. Navy]]'s history.  The demand for [[general-purpose bomb]]s (e.g., \"iron bombs\") greatly exceeded production. The inventory of bombs dwindled throughout 1966 and became critically low by 1967.<ref name=cox/> This was particularly true for the new {{convert|1000|lb|abbr=on|0}} [[Mark 83]], which the Navy favored for its power-to-size ratio. A [[CATOBAR|carrier-launched]] [[Douglas A-4 Skyhawk|A-4 Skyhawk]], the Navy's standard light attack / [[ground attack aircraft]], could carry either a single {{convert|2000|lb|kg|abbr=on|0}} bomb, or two 1,000 lb bombs. This gave it the ability to strike two separate hardened targets in a single [[sortie]], which was more effective in most circumstances.\n\nThe [[U.S. Air Force]]'s primary ground attack aircraft in Vietnam was the much heavier, land-based, [[Republic F-105 Thunderchief|F-105 Thunderchief]]. It could simultaneously carry two {{convert|3000|lb|kg|abbr=on|0}} [[Mark 118 bomb|M118]] bombs and four {{convert|750|lb|kg|abbr=on|0}} [[M117 bomb|M117]] bombs. The Air Force had a large supply of these bombs, and did not rely as heavily on the limited supply of 1,000 lb bombs as did the Navy.{{Citation needed|date = July 2014}}\n[[File:RADM John Beling.jpg|thumb|Captain [[John Kingsman Beling|Beling]] was reluctant to take delivery of the Korean War-era 16 AN-M65A1 bombs from USS ''Diamond Head'' but, faced with the prospect of having to cancel the next day's sorties, accepted them.]]\n\n=== Issues with Zuni rockets===\n\nIn addition to bombs, the ground attack aircraft carried unguided {{convert|5|in|mm|abbr=on|0}} [[Zuni (rocket)|Mk-32 \"Zuni\"]] rockets. These rockets were in wide use although they had a reputation for electrical difficulties and accidental firing.<ref name=\"invespart2\"/> It was common for aircraft to launch with six or more rocket packs, each containing four rockets.<ref name=\"invespart2\"/>\n\n=== Specialized fire-fighting teams ===\n\nBased on lessons learned during Japanese attacks on vessels during World War II, most sailors on board ships after World War II received training in fighting shipboard fires. These lessons were gradually lost and by 1967, the U.S. Navy had reverted to the Japanese model at [[Battle of Midway|Midway]] and relied on specialized, highly trained damage control and fire-fighting teams.<ref name=skyhawk/>\n\nThe damage control team specializing in on-deck firefighting for ''Forrestal'' was Damage Control Team No. 8, led by [[Chief petty officer|Chief]] [[Aviation boatswain's mate|Aviation Boatswain's Mate]] Gerald Farrier. They had been shown films during training of Navy ordnance tests demonstrating how a 1,000 lb bomb could be directly exposed to a jet fuel fire for a full ten minutes and still be extinguished and cooled without an explosive [[Cooking off|cook-off]].<ref name=freeman>{{cite book |last=Freeman |first=Gregory A. |title=Sailors to the End: The Deadly Fire on the USS Forrestal and the Heroes Who Fought It |publisher=HarperCollins |year=2004 |isbn=978-0060936907}}</ref>{{rp|126}} However, these tests were conducted using the new Mark 83 1,000 lb bombs, which featured relatively stable [[Composition H6]] explosive and thicker, heat-resistant cases, compared to their predecessors. Because it is [[insensitive munitions|relatively insensitive]] to heat, shock and electricity, Composition H6 is still used as of {{CURRENTYEAR}} in many types of naval ordnance. It is also designed to [[deflagrate]] instead of [[detonate]] when it reaches its ignition point in a fire, either melting the case and producing no explosion at all, or, at most, a subsonic [[low explosive|low order detonation]] at a fraction of its normal power.<ref name=freeman/>{{rp|85}}\n\n=== Unstable ordnance received ===\n\nOn 28 July, the day before the accident, ''Forrestal'' was resupplied with ordnance by the [[ammunition ship]] {{USS|Diamond Head|AE-19|6}}. The load included sixteen 1,000 lb AN/M65A1 \"fat boy\" bombs (so nicknamed because of their short, rotund shape), which ''Diamond Head'' had picked up from [[Subic Bay Naval Base]] and were intended for the next day's second bombing sortie. Some of the batch of AN-M65A1s ''Forrestal'' received were more than a decade old, having spent a portion of that exposed to the heat and humidity of [[Okinawa]] or [[Guam]],<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=DhhnAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT136#v=onepage&q&f=false |title= Dangerous Games: Faces, Incidents, and Casualties of the Cold War |first1= Scott |last1= Baron |first2= James |last2= Wise, Jr |publisher= Naval Institute Press |year= 2013 |isbn= 978-1612514529 |page= 136 |access-date= 20 July 2015 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160512051957/https://books.google.com/books?id=DhhnAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT136#v=onepage&q&f=false |archive-date= 12 May 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> eventually being improperly stored in open-air [[Quonset hut]]s at a disused [[ammunition dump]] on the periphery of Subic Bay Naval Base. Unlike the thick-cased Mark 83 bombs filled with Composition H6, the AN/M65A1 bombs were thin-skinned and filled with [[Composition B]], an older explosive with greater [[sensitivity (explosives)|shock and heat sensitivity]].<ref name=fear>{{Cite web |url=https://nationalinterest.org/feature/us-navy-aircraft-carriers-greatest-fear-its-not-russia-or-22055 |title=A U.S. Navy Aircraft Carrier's Greatest Fear (And It's Not Russia or China) |access-date=12 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731090904/https://nationalinterest.org/feature/us-navy-aircraft-carriers-greatest-fear-its-not-russia-or-22055 |archive-date=31 July 2018 |url-status=live |date=26 August 2017 }}</ref>\n\nComposition B also had the dangerous tendency to become more powerful (up to 50% by weight) and more sensitive if it was old or improperly stored. ''Forrestal''{{'}}s ordnance handlers had never even seen an AN/M65A1 before, and to their shock, the bombs delivered from ''Diamond Head'' were in terrible condition; coated with \"decades of accumulated rust and grime\" and still in their original packing crates (now moldy and rotten); some were stamped with production dates as early as 1953. Most dangerous of all, several bombs were seen to be leaking liquid [[paraffin wax|paraffin]] [[phlegmatized|phlegmatizing agent]] from their seams, an unmistakable sign that the bomb's explosive filler had degenerated with excessive age, and exposure to heat and moisture.<ref name=freeman/>{{rp|87}}<ref name=navylive>{{cite web |title=The Forrestal Fire |first1=John D. |last1=Burlage |url=http://www.navy.mil/navydata/nav_legacy.asp?id=73 |website=Navy News Service |accessdate=23 July 2018 |language=en |date=28 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723064421/http://www.navy.mil/navydata/nav_legacy.asp?id=73 |archive-date=23 July 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=fear/>\n\nAccording to Lieutenant R. R. \"Rocky\" Pratt, a [[naval aviator]] attached to [[VFA-106|VA-106]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.va106vf62.org/gladiator_website_007.htm |title=Gladiator Helmet |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=Gladiator Reunion Group |accessdate=13 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170421060324/http://www.va106vf62.org/gladiator_website_007.htm |archive-date=21 April 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> the concern felt by ''Forrestal''{{'}}s ordnance handlers was striking, with many afraid to even handle the bombs; one officer wondered out loud if they would survive the shock of a [[aircraft catapult|catapult-assisted launch]] without spontaneously detonating, and others suggested they immediately jettison them.<ref name=freeman/>{{rp|86}} ''Forrestal''{{'}}s ordnance officers reported the situation up the chain of command to the ship's commanding officer, Captain [[John Kingsman Beling|John Beling]], and informed him the bombs were, in their assessment, an imminent danger to the ship and should be immediately jettisoned overboard.<ref name=skyhawk/><ref name=cox/>\n\nFaced with this, but still needing 1,000 lb bombs for the next day's missions, Beling demanded ''Diamond Head'' take the AN-M65A1s back in exchange for new Mark 83s,<ref name=freeman/>{{rp|88}} but was told by ''Diamond Head'' that they had none to give him. The AN-M65A1 bombs had been returned to service specifically because there were not enough Mark 83s to go around. According to one crew member on ''Diamond Head'', when they had arrived at Subic Bay to pick up their load of ordnance for the carriers, the base personnel who had prepared the AN-M65A1 bombs for transfer assumed ''Diamond Head'' had been ordered to dump them at sea on the way back to Yankee Station. When notified that the bombs were actually destined for active service in the carrier fleet, the commanding officer of the naval ordnance detachment at Subic Bay was so shocked that he initially refused the transfer, believing a paperwork mistake had been made. At the risk of delaying ''Diamond Head''{{'}}s departure, he refused to sign the transfer forms until receiving written orders from [[CINCPAC]] on the [[teleprinter]], explicitly absolving his detachment of responsibility for the bombs' terrible condition.<ref name=cox/>\n\n=== Unstable bombs stored on deck ===\n\nWith orders to conduct strike missions over North Vietnam the next day, and with no replacement bombs available, Captain Beling reluctantly concluded that he had no choice but to accept the AN-M65A1 bombs in their current condition.<ref name=skyhawk/><ref name=\"dougherty\">{{cite web |title=Bud Dougherty Collection: Disaster on the USS Forrestal |url=https://arlingtonhistoricalsociety.org/2017/06/bud-dougherty-collection-disaster-on-the-uss-forrestal/ |website=Arlington Historical Society |accessdate=26 July 2018 |date=18 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726072002/https://arlingtonhistoricalsociety.org/2017/06/bud-dougherty-collection-disaster-on-the-uss-forrestal/ |archive-date=26 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"collins\">{{cite web |last1=Collins |first1=Elizabeth M. |title=Fire Aboard Ship |url=http://www.navy.mil/ah_online/ftrStory.asp?id=101670 |website=navy.mil |publisher=All Hands |accessdate=23 July 2018 |language=en |date=27 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723064200/http://www.navy.mil/ah_online/ftrStory.asp?id=101670 |archive-date=23 July 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In one concession to the demands of the ordnance handlers, Beling agreed to store all 16 bombs alone on deck in the \"bomb farm\" area between the starboard rail and the carrier's island until they were loaded for the next day's missions. Standard procedure was to store them in the ship's magazine with the rest of the air wing's ordnance; had they been stored as standard, an accidental detonation could easily have destroyed the ship.<ref name=\"freeman\"/>{{rp|273\u201374}}\n\n==Fire and explosions==\n\nWhile preparing for the second sortie of the day, the aft portion of the flight deck was packed wing-to-wing with twelve A-4E Skyhawk, seven [[McDonnell Douglas F-4 Phantom II|F-4B Phantom II]], and two [[North American A-5 Vigilante|Vigilante]] aircraft. A total of 27 aircraft were on deck, fully loaded with bombs, rockets, ammunition, and fuel. Several tons of bombs were stored on wooden pallets on deck in the bomb farm.<ref name=readiness>{{cite web |title=How the 1967 Fire on USS ''Forrestal'' Improved Future U.S. Navy Damage Control Readiness |url=http://usnhistory.navylive.dodlive.mil/2017/07/28/how-the-1967-fire-on-uss-forrestal-improved-future-u-s-navy-damage-control-readiness/ |website=The Sextant |accessdate=26 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726103731/http://usnhistory.navylive.dodlive.mil/2017/07/28/how-the-1967-fire-on-uss-forrestal-improved-future-u-s-navy-damage-control-readiness/ |archive-date=26 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> An F-4B Phantom II (No. 110, BuNo 153061), flown by Lieutenant Commander James E. Bangert and Lieutenant (JG) Lawrence E. McKay from [[VFA-11|VF-11]],<ref name=\"DANFS\"/> was positioned on the aft starboard corner of the deck, pointing about 45 degrees across the ship.<ref name=\"DANFS\"/> It was armed with LAU-10 underwing rocket pods, each containing four unguided {{convert|5|in|mm|abbr=on|1}} [[Zuni (rocket)|Mk-32 \"Zuni\" rockets]]. The Zuni was protected from launching by a safety pin that was only to be removed prior to launch from the catapult.<ref name=navylive/><ref name=\"invespart2\"/>{{rp|57}}\n\n=== Zuni rocket launched ===\n\nAt about 10:51 (local time) on 29 July, an electrical power surge in Phantom No. 110 occurred during the switch from external to internal power. The electrical surge caused one of the four 5-inch Mk-32 Zuni unguided rockets in a pod on external stores station 2 (port inboard station) to fire.<ref name=cox>{{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Samuel J. |title=H-008-6 USS Forrestal Disaster |url=https://www.history.navy.mil/content/history/nhhc/about-us/leadership/director/directors-corner/h-grams/h-gram-008/h-008-6.html |website=www.history.navy.mil |accessdate=26 July 2018 |date=July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190331190626/https://www.history.navy.mil/content/history/nhhc/about-us/leadership/director/directors-corner/h-grams/h-gram-008/h-008-6.html |archive-date=31 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The rocket was later determined to be missing the rocket safety pin, allowing the rocket to launch.<ref name=navylive/> The rocket flew about {{convert|100|ft}} across the flight deck, likely severing the arm of a crewman, and ruptured a {{convert|400|gal|adj=on}} wing-mounted external fuel tank on a Skyhawk from Attack Squadron 46 ([[VA-46 (U.S. Navy)|VA-46]]) awaiting launch.<ref name=\"DANFS\"/><ref name=usnav_investigation>{{cite web |author=US Navy |url=http://www.jag.navy.mil/library/investigations/USS%20FORRESTAL%20FIRE%2012%20AUG%2069%20PT%201.pdf |title= Fire and explosions aboard USS ''Forrestal'' (CV 59) |date=19 September 1967 |publisher=Judge Advocate General |access-date=23 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228152838/http://www.jag.navy.mil/library/investigations/USS%20FORRESTAL%20FIRE%2012%20AUG%2069%20PT%201.pdf |archive-date=28 December 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"invespart2\"/>{{rp|34, 93}}\n\n[[File:CVA-59 fire aft deck plan.png|thumb|left|A drawing of the stern of ''Forrestal'' showing the spotting of aircraft at the time. Likely source of the Zuni was F-4 No. 110. White's and McCain's aircraft (A-4s No. 405 and 416, respectively) are in the right-hand circle.]]\n\n=== Aircraft struck ===\n[[File:USS Forrestal A-4 Skyhawk burning.png|thumb|In the first moments of the disaster, an A-4 Skyhawk burns immediately after its fuel tank is ruptured by a Zuni rocket.]]\nThe official Navy investigation identified the Skyhawk struck by the Zuni as aircraft No. 405, piloted by Lieutenant Commander Fred D. White.<ref name=Stewart/><ref>{{cite news |first=Mike |last=Cherney |title=Veterans salute sailors killed aboard carrier |url=http://content.hamptonroads.com/story.cfm?story=129305&ran=106811 |location=Hampton Roads |work=The Virginian Pilot |pages= 1, 8 |date=28 July 2007 |access-date=28 July 2007|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070926233824/http://content.hamptonroads.com/story.cfm?story=129305&ran=106811 |archivedate = 26 September 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> Lieutenant Commander [[John McCain]] stated in his 1999 book ''[[Faith of My Fathers]]'' that the missile struck his aircraft, alongside White's A-4 Skyhawk. \"On that Saturday morning in July, as I sat in the cockpit of my A-4 preparing to take off, a rocket hit the fuel tank under my airplane.\"<ref name=popmech>{{cite web |last1=McCain |first1=John |title=The 1967 Aircraft Carrier Fire That Nearly Killed John McCain |url=https://www.popularmechanics.com/military/aviation/a14416145/fire-on-the-flight-deck/ |website=Popular Mechanics |accessdate=27 July 2018 |date=September 1974 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180727085322/https://www.popularmechanics.com/military/aviation/a14416145/fire-on-the-flight-deck/ |archive-date=27 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Later accounts relying on his book also state that the rocket struck his A-4 Skyhawk.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ringle |first1=Ken |title=A Navy Ship's Trial by Fire |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1997/08/02/a-navy-ships-trial-by-fire/676aab23-29ee-4d3e-b18f-e1e8894b05c1/?noredirect=on |website=Washington Post |accessdate=23 July 2018 |date=2 August 1997 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723122506/https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1997/08/02/a-navy-ships-trial-by-fire/676aab23-29ee-4d3e-b18f-e1e8894b05c1/?noredirect=on&utm_term=.d75c77c87a95 |archive-date=23 July 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=thisday>{{cite web |title=Rocket causes deadly fire on aircraft carrier - Jul 29, 1967 - HISTORY.com |url=https://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/rocket-causes-deadly-fire-on-aircraft-carrier |website=HISTORY.com |accessdate=26 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726040954/https://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/rocket-causes-deadly-fire-on-aircraft-carrier |archive-date=26 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Forrestal, Navy's 1st 'supercarrier,' changes hands in one-cent transaction |url=https://www.stripes.com/news/navy/forrestal-navy-s-1st-supercarrier-changes-hands-in-one-cent-transaction-1.248584 |website=Stars and Stripes |accessdate=26 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726073847/https://www.stripes.com/news/navy/forrestal-navy-s-1st-supercarrier-changes-hands-in-one-cent-transaction-1.248584 |archive-date=26 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe Zuni rocket's warhead safety mechanism prevented it from detonating. The rocket broke apart on impact with the external fuel tank.<ref name=\"invespart2\"/>{{rp|34}} The highly flammable [[JP-5]] fuel spread on the deck under White's and McCain's A-4s, ignited by numerous fragments of burning rocket propellant, and causing an instantaneous [[conflagration]]. A sailor standing about 100 feet forward was struck by a fragment of the Zuni or the exploding fuel tank. A fragment also punctured the centerline external fuel tank of A-4 #310, positioned just aft of the jet blast deflector of catapult number 3. The resulting fire was fanned by {{convert|32|knot|adj=on|lk=in}} winds and the exhaust of at least three jets.<ref name=usnav_investigation/><ref name=\"collins\"/> Fire quarters and then [[general quarters]] were sounded at 10:52 and 10:53. Condition ZEBRA was declared at 10:59, requiring all hands to secure the ship for maximum survivability, including closing the fire-proof steel doors that separate the ship's compartments.<ref>{{cite web |title=Material Conditions of Readiness - 14325_341 |url=http://navyadvancement.tpub.com/14325/css/Material-Conditions-Of-Readiness-341.htm |website=navyadvancement.tpub.com |accessdate=26 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817083423/http://navyadvancement.tpub.com/14325/css/Material-Conditions-Of-Readiness-341.htm |archive-date=17 August 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe official report states that one [[Korean War]]-era 1,000 lb AN-M65 bomb fell from an A-4 Skyhawk to the deck;<ref name=usnav_investigation/><ref name=\"browning\">{{cite web |last1=Browning |first1=LCdr. Robert \"Bo\" |title=Personal account of the USS Forrestal fire, July 29, 1967 |url=http://www.safetycenter.navy.mil/MEDIA/approach/theydidwhat/Forrestal.htm |publisher=Navy Safety Center |accessdate=23 July 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040206055916/http://www.safetycenter.navy.mil/MEDIA/approach/theydidwhat/Forrestal.htm |archivedate=6 February 2004}}</ref><ref name=chinfo>{{cite web |title=The Forrestal Fire |url=http://www.chinfo.navy.mil/navpalib/ships/carriers/histories/cv59-forrestal/forrestal-fire.html |accessdate=23 July 2018 |archivedate= 8 February 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060208032244/http://www.chinfo.navy.mil/navpalib/ships/carriers/histories/cv59-forrestal/forrestal-fire.html}}</ref> other reports say two.<ref name=\"dougherty\"/><ref name=skyhawk>{{cite web |title=U.S.S. ''Forrestal'' Fire 1967 {{!}} A-4 Skyhawk Association |url=http://a4skyhawk.info/article-unit/cva59-1967fire |website=a4skyhawk.info |accessdate=26 July 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726071859/http://a4skyhawk.info/article-unit/cva59-1967fire |archive-date=26 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The bomb fell in a pool of burning fuel between White's and McCain's aircraft.\n\n[[Damage Control]] Team No. 8, led by Chief Gerald W. Farrier, were the first responders to any incident on the flight deck. They immediately took action. Farrier, without taking the time to locate and put on protective clothing, immediately attempted to smother the bomb with a [[Purple-K|PKP]] fire extinguisher, attempting to delay the fuel fire from spreading and give the pilots time to escape their aircraft.<ref name=\"navylive\"/> Based on their training, the team believed they had a ten-minute window to extinguish the fire before the bombs casing would melt resulting in a low-order explosion.<ref name=\"heroes\"/>\n\n[[File:USS_Forrestal_fire_1_1967.jpg|thumb|A bomb explodes on the aft deck of ''Forrestal'']]\n\nThe pilots, preparing to launch, were strapped into their aircraft. When the fire started and quickly spread, they immediately attempted to escape their aircraft. McCain, pilot of A-4 Skyhawk side No. 416, next to White's, was among the first to notice the flames, and escaped by scrambling down the nose of his A-4 and jumping off the [[Aerial refueling#Probe-and-drogue|refueling probe]]. Lt. Cmdr. Robert \"Bo\" Browning, in an A-4E Skyhawk on the port side, escaped by crossing the flight deck and ducking under the tails of F-4B Phantoms spotted along the starboard side.<ref name=\"browning\"/> CVW-17 operations officer, Lt. Cmdr. Herbert A. Hope of VA-46, escaped by jumping out of the Skyhawk cockpit and rolling off the flight deck and into the starboard man-overboard net. He went to the hangar deck and took command of a firefighting team.\n\n=== Bombs detonate ===\n\nDespite Farrier's constant effort to cool the bomb that had fallen to the deck, the casing suddenly split open and the explosive began to burn brightly.<ref name=usnav_investigation/> Farrier. recognizing that a lethal cook-off was imminent, shouted for his [[damage controlman|firefighters]] to withdraw, but the bomb detonated\u2014one minute and 36 seconds after the start of the fire.<ref name=freeman/>{{rp|123\u201324}} The unstable Composition B in the old bombs enhanced the power of the explosions.<ref name=skyhawk/> Thirty-five personnel were in close proximity to the blast. Two fire control teams were virtually destroyed; Farrier and all but three of his men were killed instantly. Twenty-seven men were injured.<ref name=usnav_investigation/>\n\n\"I saw a dozen people running... into the fire, just before the bomb cooked off,\" Lt. Cmdr. Browning later said.<ref name=\"browning\"/><ref name=\"heroes\"/> McCain saw another pilot on fire, and turned to help him, when the first bomb detonated. McCain was knocked backwards 10 feet, struck by shrapnel and wounded. White managed to get out of his burning aircraft but was killed by the detonation of the first bomb.<ref name=\"heroes\">{{cite web |title=A Ship Full of Heroes |url=http://www.news.navy.mil:80/media/allhands/acrobat/ah196711.pdf |publisher=All Hands |accessdate=24 July 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040119140044/http://www.news.navy.mil/media/allhands/acrobat/ah196711.pdf |archivedate=19 January 2004 |pages=7\u201311 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Not all of the pilots were able to get out of their aircraft in time. Lt Ken McMillen escaped. LT(JG) Don Dameworth and LT(JG) David Dollarhide were injured escaping their aircraft. Lt. Cmdrs Gerry Stark and Dennis Barton were missing.<ref name=\"heroes\"/>\n\n=== Fire enters lower decks ===\n\nThe first bomb detonation destroyed White's and McCain's aircraft, blew a crater in the [[armored flight deck]], and sprayed the deck and crew with [[Fragmentation (weaponry)|bomb fragments]] and shrapnel from the destroyed aircraft. Burning fuel poured through the hole in the deck into occupied berthing compartments below. In the tightly packed formation on the aft deck, every aircraft, all fully fueled and bomb-laden, was damaged. All seven F-4s caught fire.<ref name=skyhawk/>\n\nLieutenant James J. Campbell recoiled for a few moments in stunned dismay as burning torches tumbled toward him, until their screams stirred him to action.<ref name=DANFS/> Several men jumped or were blown into the ocean. Neighboring ships came alongside and pulled the men from the water.<ref name=\"heroes\"/> When Browning got back on deck, he recalled, \"The port quarter of the flight deck where I was is no longer there.\"<ref name=DANFS/>\n\nTwo more of the unstable 1,000 lb bombs exploded 10 seconds after the first, and a fourth blew up 44 seconds after that. A total of ten bombs exploded during the fire.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pnj.com/story/news/2017/07/29/uss-forrestal-fire-commemoration-reminder-heroism-service-and-sacrifice/521042001/|title=USS Forrestal fire commemoration a reminder of 'heroism, service and sacrifice' |date=29 July 2017 |work=Pensacola News Journal|access-date=2018-10-06|language=en}}</ref> Bodies and debris were hurled as far as the bow of the ship.\n\nIn less than five minutes, seven or eight 1,000-pound bombs,<ref name=skyhawk/><ref name=\"beauregard\"/> one 750-pound bomb, one {{convert|500|lb|adj=on|0}} bomb, and several missile and rocket warheads heated by the fire exploded with varying degrees of violence.<ref name=\"beauregard\">{{cite web |last1=Beauregard |first1=Raymond L |title=The USS Forrestal (CVA-59) fire and munition explosions {{!}} The History of Insensitive Munitions |url=http://www.insensitivemunitions.org/history/the-uss-forrestal-cva-59-fire-and-munition-explosions/ |website=www.insensitivemunitions.org |accessdate=26 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726103548/http://www.insensitivemunitions.org/history/the-uss-forrestal-cva-59-fire-and-munition-explosions/ |archive-date=26 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Several of the explosions of the 1,000-pound Korean War-era AN-M65 Composition B bombs were estimated to be as much as 50% more powerful than a standard 1,000-pound bomb, due to the badly degraded Composition B.<ref name=usnav_investigation/> The ninth explosion was attributed to a [[sympathetic detonation]] between an AN-M65 and a newer 500 lb [[M117 bomb|M117]] H6 bomb that were positioned next to each other. The other H6-based bombs performed as designed and either burned on the deck or were jettisoned, but did not detonate under the heat of the fires.<ref name=skyhawk/> The ongoing detonations prevented fire suppression efforts during the first critical minutes of the disaster.<ref name=usnav_investigation/>\n\nThe explosions tore seven holes in the flight deck. About {{convert|40000|gal}} of burning jet fuel from ruptured aircraft tanks poured across the deck and through the holes in the deck into the aft hangar bay and berthing compartments. The explosions and fire killed fifty night crew personnel who were sleeping in berthing compartments below the aft portion of the flight deck. Forty-one additional crew members were killed in internal compartments in the aft portion of ''Forrestal''.<ref name=skyhawk/><ref name=usnav_investigation/>\n\n[[File:USS_Forrestal_fire_RA-5Cs_burning_1967.jpg|thumb|Two North American RA-5C Vigilante aircraft of heavy reconnaissance squadron RVAH-11 Checkertails are burning on the starboard side aft of the island, while crewmen remove AGM-45 Shrike missiles in the foreground.]]\n\nPersonnel from all over the ship rallied to fight the fires and control further damage. They pushed aircraft, missiles, rockets, bombs, and burning fragments over the side. Sailors manually jettisoned numerous 250 and 500 lb bombs by rolling them along the deck and off the side. Sailors without training in firefighting and damage control took over for the depleted damage control teams. Unknowingly, inexperienced hose teams using seawater washed away the efforts of others attempting to smother the fire with foam.<ref name=\"heroes\"/><ref name=DANFS/>\n\n=== Fires controlled ===\n[[File:USS Forrestal explosion 29 July 1967.jpg|thumb|The initial explosions killed or seriously injured most of the ship's specially trained damage control and firefighting teams, requiring the rest of the crew to step in and combat the subsequent fires.]]\n\nThe destroyer {{USS|George K. MacKenzie|DD-836|6}} pulled men from the water and directed its fire hoses on the burning ship. Another destroyer, {{USS|Rupertus|DD-851|6}}, maneuvered as close as {{convert|20|feet}} to ''Forrestal'' for 90 minutes, directing her own on-board fire hoses at the burning flight and hangar deck on the starboard side, and at the port-side aft 5-inch gun mount.<ref name=\"logs\" /> Rear Admiral and Task Group commander Harvey P. Lanham, aboard ''Forrestal'', called the actions of ''Rupertus'' commanding officer Commander Edwin Burke<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navsource.org/archives/05/851.htm |title=USS ''Rupertus'' (DD-851) |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=navsource.org |accessdate=13 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150821083929/http://www.navsource.org/archives/05/851.htm |archive-date=21 August 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> an \"act of magnificent seamanship\".<ref name=\"logs\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navsource.org/archives/02/cv-59/59f-0729.htm |title=The Forrestal Fire, July 29, 1967 Ship's Logs |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=14 November 2011 |website=navsource.org |accessdate=13 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150724122601/http://www.navsource.org/archives/02/cv-59/59f-0729.htm |archive-date=24 July 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> At 11:47 am, ''Forrestal'' reported the flight deck fire was under control. About 30 minutes later, they had put out the flight deck fires. Fire fighting crews continued to fight fires below deck for many more hours.<ref name=\"logs\" />\n\nUndetonated bombs were continually found during the afternoon. [[Lieutenant (junior grade)|LT(JG)]] Robert Cates, the carrier's explosive ordnance demolition officer, recounted later how he had \"noticed that there was a 500-pound bomb and a 750-pound bomb in the middle of the flight deck... that were still smoking. They hadn't detonated or anything; they were just setting there smoking. So I went up and defused them and had them jettisoned.\" Another sailor volunteered to be lowered by line through a hole in the flight deck to defuse a live bomb that had dropped to the 03 level\u2014even though the compartment was still on fire and full of smoke. Later on, Cates had himself lowered into the compartment to attach a line to the bomb so it could be hauled up to the deck and jettisoned.<ref name=chinfo/>\n\nThroughout the day, the ship's medical staff worked in dangerous conditions to assist their comrades. The number of casualties quickly overwhelmed the ship's medical teams, and ''Forrestal'' was escorted by {{USS|Henry W. Tucker|DD-875|6}} to rendezvous with hospital ship {{USS|Repose|AH-16|6}} at 20:54, allowing the crew to begin transferring the dead and wounded at 22:53.<ref name=DANFS/> Firefighter Milt Crutchley said, \"The worst was going back into the burned-out areas later and finding your dead and wounded shipmates.\" He said it was extremely difficult to remove charred, blackened bodies locked in [[rigor mortis]] \"while maintaining some sort of dignity for your fallen comrades.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ringle |first1=Ken |title=A Navy Ship's Trial by Fire |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1997/08/02/a-navy-ships-trial-by-fire/676aab23-29ee-4d3e-b18f-e1e8894b05c1/?noredirect=on |website=Washington Post |accessdate=25 July 2018 |date=2 August 1997 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180725054947/https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1997/08/02/a-navy-ships-trial-by-fire/676aab23-29ee-4d3e-b18f-e1e8894b05c1/?noredirect=on&utm_term=.4836e6836cb2 |archive-date=25 July 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAt 5:05, a [[Muster (military)|muster]] of ''Forrestal'' crewmen\u2014both in the carrier and aboard other ships\u2014was begun. It took many hours to account for the ship's crew. Wounded and dead had been transferred to other ships, and some men were missing, either burned beyond recognition or blown overboard.  At 6:44&nbsp;pm, fires were still burning in the ship's carpenter shop and in the aft compartments. At 8:33 pm, the fires in the 02 and 03 levels were contained, but the areas were still too hot to enter. Fire fighting was greatly hampered because of smoke and heat. Crew members cut additional holes in the flight deck to help fight fires in the compartments below. At 12:20&nbsp;am, July 30, 14 hours after the fires had begun, all the fires were controlled. ''Forrestal'' crew members continued to put out hot spots, clear smoke, and cool hot steel on the 02 and 03 levels. The fires were declared out at 4:00 am.<ref name=chinfo/><ref name=DANFS/>\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[File:USS Forrestal about one month after 1967 fire.jpg|thumb|''Forrestal'' put into Cubi Point in the Philippines to be patched before returning to the United States, where she was drydocked for eight months of repairs.]]\n\nThe fire left 134 men dead<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.manchestertimes.com/?p=3792 | title=Forty-five years later, veteran remembers worst naval disaster since WW II | work=Manchester Times| date=24 July 2012 | accessdate=12 April 2015 | author=Coffelt, John | quote=Before the sun came up that Saturday morning, Seaman Kenneth Dyke fell into the warm waters 60 miles off the Gulf of Tonkin where the ship was taking part in operations at Yankee Station, according to the online records of the ship's log. | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518103515/http://www.manchestertimes.com/?p=3792 | archive-date=18 May 2015 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> and 161 more injured.<ref name=Stewart/> It was the worst loss of life on a U.S. Navy ship since World War II.<ref name=thisday/> Of the 73 aircraft aboard the carrier, 21 were destroyed and 40 were damaged.<ref name=navymil>{{cite web |title=The Catastrophic Fire on Board USS ''Forrestal'' |url=https://www.history.navy.mil/browse-by-topic/disasters-and-phenomena/forrestal-fire.html |website=www.history.navy.mil |accessdate=25 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170713233406/https://www.history.navy.mil/browse-by-topic/disasters-and-phenomena/forrestal-fire.html |archive-date=13 July 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nTwenty-one aircraft were stricken from naval inventory: seven F-4B Phantom IIs, eleven A-4E Skyhawks, and three [[North American A-5 Vigilante|RA-5C Vigilantes]].<ref name=\"DANFS\"/>\n\nThe ship's chaplains held a memorial service in Hangar Bay One for the crewmen which was attended by more than 2,000 of ''Forrestal's'' crew.\n\n=== Temporary repairs ===\n[[File:Forrestal limping home '67.JPG|thumb|Damage sustained to ''Forrestal'']]\nOn 31 July, ''Forrestal'' arrived at [[Naval Air Station Cubi Point]] in the Philippines, to undertake repairs sufficient to allow the ship to return to the United States. During welcoming ceremonies, a fire alarm signal alerted crews to a fire in mattresses within the burned-out compartments.<ref name=popmech/>\n\n=== Investigation begun ===\n\nA special group, the Aircraft Carrier Safety Review Panel, was convened on 15 August in the Philippines. Owing to the necessity of returning the ship to the United States for repair, the panel acted quickly to interview personnel on board the ship.<ref name=tragic/>\n\n===Ordnance issues found ===\n[[File:USS Forrestal (CV-59) cost of the fire.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Sailors carefully lower the first of their shipmates killed in the fire to the Leyte Pier at [[Naval Air Station Cubi Point]] in the Philippines.]]\n\nInvestigators identified issues with [[stray voltage]] in the circuitry of the LAU-10 rocket launchers and Zuni missiles. They also identified issues with the aging 1,000 lb \"fat bombs\" carried for the strike, which were discovered to have dated from the Korean War in 1953.<ref name=DANFS/>\n\n=== Safety procedures overridden ===\n\nThe board of investigation stated, \"Poor and outdated doctrinal and technical documentation of ordnance and aircraft equipment and procedures, evident at all levels of command, was a contributing cause of the accidental rocket firing.\" However, the doctrine and procedures employed were not unique to ''Forrestal''. Other carriers had problems with the Zuni rockets.<ref name=cox/>\n\nThe investigation found that safety regulations should have prevented the Zuni rocket from firing. A triple ejector rack (TER) electrical safety pin was designed to prevent any electrical signal from reaching the rockets before the aircraft was launched, but it was also known that high winds could sometimes catch the attached tags and blow them free. In addition to the pin, a \"pigtail\" connected the electrical wiring of the missile to the rocket pod. US Navy regulations required the pigtail be connected only when the aircraft was attached to the catapult and ready to launch, but the ordnance officers found this slowed down the launch rate.<ref name=\"invespart2\"/>{{rp|57}}\n\nThe Navy investigation found that four weeks before the fire, ''Forrestal''{{'}}s Weapons Coordination Board, along with members of the Weapons Planning Board, held a meeting to discuss the issue of attaching the pigtail at the catapult. Launches were sometimes delayed when a crew member had difficulty completing the connection. They agreed on a deviation from standard procedure. In a memorandum of the meeting, they agreed to \"Allow ordnance personnel to connect pigtails 'in the pack', prior to taxi, leaving only safety pin removal at the cat.\" The memo, written on 8 July 1967, was circulated to the ship's operations officer. But the memo and the decision were never communicated to Captain Beling, the ship's commanding officer, who was required to approve such decisions.<ref name=\"invespart3\">{{cite web |title=Fire and Explosion aboard USS ''Forrestal'' (CVA-59) Part 2 |url=http://www.jag.navy.mil/library/investigations/USS%20FORRESTAL%20FIRE%2012%20AUG%2069%20PT%202.pdf |accessdate=26 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170109101458/http://www.jag.navy.mil/library/investigations/USS%20FORRESTAL%20FIRE%2012%20AUG%2069%20PT%202.pdf |archive-date=9 January 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{rp|65}}\n\n=== Causes identified ===\n\nThe official inquiry found that the ordnance crew acted immediately on the Weapons Coordination Board's decision. They found that the pigtail was connected early, that the TER pin on the faulty Zuni missile was likely blown free, and that the missile fired when a power surge occurred as the pilot transferred his systems from external to internal power.<ref name=navylive/><ref name=\"invespart2\"/>{{rp|57}} Their report concluded that a ZUNI rocket on the portside TER-7 on external stores station 2 of F-4B No. 110 of VF-11, spotted on the extreme starboard quarter of the flight deck, struck A-4 No. 405, piloted by Lt. Cmdr. Fred D. White, on the port side of the aft deck. The accidental firing was due to the simultaneous malfunction of three components: CA42282 pylon electrical disconnect, TER-7 safety switch, and LAU-10/A shorting device. They concluded that the CA42282 pylon electrical disconnect had a design defect, and found that the TER-7 safety pin was poorly designed, making it easy to confuse with ordnance pins used in the AERO-7 Sparrow Launcher, which if used by mistake would not operate effectively.<ref name=\"invespart2\">{{cite web|title=Official investigation Part 3|url=http://www.jag.navy.mil/library/investigations/USS%20FORRESTAL%20FIRE%2012%20AUG%2069%20PT%203.pdf|publisher=Judge Advocate General|accessdate=27 August 2018|date=19 September 1967|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920103030/http://www.jag.navy.mil/library/investigations/USS%20FORRESTAL%20FIRE%2012%20AUG%2069%20PT%203.pdf|archive-date=20 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Drydock repairs ===\n\nWhen temporary repairs in the Philippines were completed, ''Forrestal'' departed on 11 August, arriving at [[Naval Station Mayport]] in Florida on 12 September to disembark the remaining aircraft and air group personnel stationed in Florida. Two days later, ''Forrestal'' returned to Norfolk to be welcomed home by over 3,000 family members and friends of the crew, gathered on Pier 12 and onboard {{USS|Randolph|CV-15|2}}, ''Forrestal''{{'}}s host ship.<ref name=DANFS/>\n[[File:Forrestal fire 40th Anniversary memorial ceremony flags and photos.jpg|thumb|left|Flags and photos displayed at a 40th anniversary memorial ceremony in Norfolk, Virginia.]]\n\nFrom 19 September 1967 to 8 April 1968, ''Forrestal'' underwent repairs in [[Norfolk Naval Shipyard]], beginning with removal of the starboard deck-edge elevator, which was stuck in place. It had to be cut from the ship while being supported by the shipyard's [[Crane (machine)#Hammerhead|hammerhead crane]]. The carrier occupied [[drydock]] number 8 from 21 September 1967, until 10 February 1968, displacing {{USS|John King|DDG-3|6}}, an oil tanker, and a minesweeper that were occupying the drydock. During the post-fire refit, {{convert|175 |feet}} of the flight deck was replaced, along with about 200 compartments on the 03, 02, 01 decks. The ship's four aft [[5\"/54 caliber Mark 42 gun]]s were removed. The forward four guns had been removed prior to 1962. The repair cost about $72 million (equal to more than $602 million in 2019 dollars), and took nearly five months to complete.<ref>{{cite web |title=The USS ''Forrestal'' (CVA-59) fire and munition explosions {{!}} The History of Insensitive Munitions |url=http://www.insensitivemunitions.org/history/the-uss-forrestal-cva-59-fire-and-munition-explosions/ |website=www.insensitivemunitions.org |accessdate=13 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726103548/http://www.insensitivemunitions.org/history/the-uss-forrestal-cva-59-fire-and-munition-explosions/ |archive-date=26 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=readiness/><ref>{{cite web |title=Aircraft Carrier Photo Index: USS ''Forrestal'' (CVA-59) |url=http://www.navsource.org/archives/02/cv-59/59f-09.htm |website=www.navsource.org |accessdate=26 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726234122/http://www.navsource.org/archives/02/cv-59/59f-09.htm |archive-date=26 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Beling reassigned ===\n\n[[John Kingsman Beling|Captain Beling]], as an Admiral-selectee, received orders to report to Washington, D.C., as the Director of Development Programs in Naval Operations, reporting to Chief of Naval Operations Admiral [[Thomas H. Moorer]]. On 18 September 1967, Captain Robert B. Baldwin assumed command of ''Forrestal''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Aircraft Carrier Photo Index: USS ''Forrestal'' (CVA-59) |url=http://www.navsource.org/archives/02/cv-59/59f-09.htm |website=www.navsource.org |accessdate=31 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726234122/http://www.navsource.org/archives/02/cv-59/59f-09.htm |archive-date=26 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> From 8 to 15 April 1968, he sailed the ship down the [[Elizabeth River (Virginia)|Elizabeth River]] and out into the waters off the [[Virginia Capes]] for post-repair trials, the ship's first time at sea in 207 days. While accomplishing trials, the ship also recorded its first arrested landing since the fire, when Commander Robert E. Ferguson, Commander, CVW-17, landed on board.<ref name=DANFS/>\n\n=== Beling absolved of responsibility ===\n\nThe Naval investigation panel's findings were released on 18 October. They concluded Beling knew that the Zuni missiles had a history of problems, and he should have made more effort to confirm that the ordnance crew was following procedure in handling the ordnance.<ref name=\"invespart2\"/> They ruled he was not responsible for the disaster, but he was nonetheless transferred to staff work, and never returned to active command.\n\nBeling was assigned temporary duty on the staff of Admiral [[Ephraim P. Holmes]], Commander-in-Chief of the U.S. Atlantic Fleet. Holmes disagreed with many portions of the Navy's report into the ''Forrestal'' disaster, including the section clearing Beling. He had Beling assigned to his staff so he could issue a letter of reprimand. By holding Beling responsible he would effectively end his career. Holmes attached the reprimand to the final report, but when Admiral Moorer endorsed the report, he ordered Admiral Holmes to rescind and remove the reprimand.<ref name=\"freeman\" /><ref name=skyhawk/>\n\nThe investigation panel recommended several changes to safety procedures aboard carriers. This included development of a remote-control fire-fighting system for the flight deck, development of more stable ordnance, improvement in survival equipment, and increased training in fire survival.<ref name=tragic>{{cite web |title=The Tragic Fire July 29, 1967 |url=http://forrestal.org:80/fidfacts/page14.htm |website=forrestal.org |accessdate=6 August 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060221012853/http://forrestal.org/fidfacts/page14.htm |archivedate=21 February 2006 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The U.S. Navy implemented safety reviews for weapons systems brought on board ships for use or for transshipment. This evaluation is still carried out by the [[Weapon System Safety|Weapon System Explosives Safety Review Board]].<ref name=cox/><ref name=freeman/>{{rp|123,124}} The fire aboard ''Forrestal'' was the second of three serious fires to strike American carriers in the 1960s.  A [[USS Oriskany fire|1966 fire]] aboard {{USS|Oriskany|CV-34|6}} killed 44 and injured 138 and a [[USS Enterprise fire|1969 fire]] aboard {{USS|Enterprise|CVN-65|6}} killed 28 and injured 314. The greatest loss of life on a U.S. Navy ship since World War II was when the destroyer {{USS|Hobson|DD-464|6}} collided with the aircraft carrier {{USS|Wasp|CV-18|6}} on 26 April 1952, breaking in half, killing 176.\n\n==Incorrect NASA report==\nA 1995 report, NASA Reference Publication 1374, incorrectly described the ''Forrestal'' fire as a result of [[electromagnetic interference]]. It states, \"a Navy jet landing on the aircraft carrier ''U.S.S. Forrestal'' experienced the uncommanded release of munitions that struck a fully armed and fueled fighter on deck... This accident was caused by the landing aircraft being illuminated by carrier based radar, and the resulting EMI sent an unwanted signal to the weapons system.\"<ref name=\"NASA 1374\">{{cite web |url=https://see.msfc.nasa.gov/sites/see.msfc.nasa.gov/files/rp-1374.pdf |title=Electronic Systems Failures and Anomalies Attributed to Electromagnetic Interference |first=R.D. |last=Leach |editor-first=M.B. |editor-last=Alexander |publisher=Marshall Space Flight Center |date=July 1995 |access-date=21 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161203053322/https://see.msfc.nasa.gov/sites/see.msfc.nasa.gov/files/rp-1374.pdf |archive-date=3 December 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{rp|7}}\n\nThis incorrect description has been cited as a [[cautionary tale]] on the importance of avoiding electromagnetic interference.<ref>David H. Harland and Ralph D. Lorenz, ''Space System Failures'', p. 240, {{ISBN|0-387-21519-0}}, Springer-Praxis, 2005</ref><ref>William Pentland, [https://www.forbes.com/sites/williampentland/2012/09/10/yes-our-gadgets-really-threaten-planes/#5288734b3599 ''Yes, Our Gadgets Really Threaten Planes''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122073059/https://www.forbes.com/sites/williampentland/2012/09/10/yes-our-gadgets-really-threaten-planes/#5288734b3599 |date=22 January 2018 }}, Forbes, 10 September 2012</ref> The report itself lacks an accurate reference to the fire. While text contains a superscript pointing to item 12 in the references section, item 12 in the reference section is to \"Von Achen, W.: ''The Apache Helicopter: An EMI Case History.'' Compliance Engineering, Fall, 1991.\"<ref name=\"NASA 1374\"/>{{rp|19}}\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:US Navy 060215-N-5330L-600 Machinist's Mate 1st Class Timothy B. Golden, looks on as his students apply newly learned skill sets in a training simulator.jpg|thumb|Machinist's Mate 1st Class Timothy B. Golden at Farrier Firefighting School, Naval Station Norfolk, observes students test their fire fighting skills in a training simulator in the basic shipboard firefighting course.]]\n\nEighteen crewmen were buried at [[Arlington National Cemetery]].<ref>{{cite web |publisher= Unofficial Arlington National Cemetery website |url= http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/ussforr.htm |title= USS Forrestal |access-date= 6 February 2008 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080503023538/http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/ussforr.htm |archive-date= 3 May 2008 |url-status=live |df= dmy-all }}</ref> Names of the dead are also listed on the [[Vietnam Veterans Memorial]].\n\nOn 29 July 2017, the USS Forrestal Association commemorated the 50th anniversary of the incident. Members of the military, survivors of the disaster, and family members gathered to memorialize those lost in this incident. Active duty personnel presented American flags to represent each sailor who died.<ref name=fifty/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Software |first1=Web Easy Professional Avanquest |title=50 Year Anniversary USS FORESTALL Fire Memorial Ceremony in Washington D.C. |url=http://www.va106vf62.org/gladiator_website_010.htm |website=www.va106vf62.org |publisher=USS FORRESTAL CVA 59 |accessdate=26 July 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726071943/http://www.va106vf62.org/gladiator_website_010.htm |archive-date=26 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe non-profit USS Forrestal Association was formed in 1990 to preserve the memory of those lost in the tragedy.<ref name=fifty>{{cite web |title=USS Forrestal Tragedy Remembered 50 Years Later |url=https://www.dvidshub.net/news/243170/uss-forrestal-tragedy-remembered-50-years-later |website=DVIDS |accessdate=25 July 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731203727/https://www.dvidshub.net/news/243170/uss-forrestal-tragedy-remembered-50-years-later |archive-date=31 July 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Farrier Fire Fighting School established===\nThe Farrier Fire Fighting School Learning Site in Norfolk, Virginia is named after Chief Gerald W. Farrier, the commander of Damage Control Team 8, who was killed in the initial explosion.<ref name=\"navylive\"/> The school hosts an annual memorial remembering the sailors who lost their lives aboard the ''Forrestal''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jackson |first1=MC3 Shane A. |title=USS Forrestal's fallen remembered at Farrier School ceremony |url=https://www.militarynews.com/norfolk-navy-flagship/oceana/news/uss-forrestal-s-fallen-remembered-at-farrier-school-ceremony/article_737f5129-f862-56a5-87a7-e56c1dafc0f4.html |website=Military News |accessdate=2 August 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180802223547/https://www.militarynews.com/norfolk-navy-flagship/oceana/news/uss-forrestal-s-fallen-remembered-at-farrier-school-ceremony/article_737f5129-f862-56a5-87a7-e56c1dafc0f4.html |archive-date=2 August 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Lessons learned===\n[[File:CVA-42 deck edge water system NAN11-69.jpg|thumb|26 May 1969, the first deck-edge spray system installed on {{USS|Franklin D. Roosevelt|CV-42|2}} as a direct result of the ''Forrestal'' fire.]]\n\nThe fire revealed that ''Forrestal'' lacked a heavy-duty, armored forklift needed to jettison aircraft, particularly heavier planes like the RA-5C Vigilante, as well as heavy or damaged ordnance.<ref name=DANFS/>\n\nThe United States Navy uses the ''Forrestal'' fire and the lessons learned from it when teaching [[damage control]] and ammunition safety. The flight-deck film of the flight operations, titled \"''Learn or Burn''\", became mandatory viewing for firefighting trainees.<ref name=DANFS/> All new Navy recruits are required to view a training video titled ''Trial by Fire: A Carrier Fights for Life'',<ref name=\"trialbyfire\">{{cite web |title= Trial by Fire: A Carrier Fights for Life |url= https://archive.org/details/gov.ntis.ava19833vnb1 |publisher= NTIS |accessdate= 15 September 2011 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110511114912/http://www.archive.org/details/gov.ntis.ava19833vnb1 |archive-date= 11 May 2011 |url-status=live |year= 1973 }}</ref><ref name=\"navylive\"/><ref name=chinfo/> produced from footage of the fire and damage control efforts, both successful and unsuccessful.\n\nFootage revealed that damage-control teams spraying [[firefighting foam]] on the deck to smother the burning fuel, which was the correct procedure, had their efforts negated by crewmen on the other side of the deck spraying seawater, which washed the foam away. The sea water worsened the situation by washing burning fuel through the holes in the flight deck and into the decks below. In response, a \"wash down\" system, which floods the flight deck with foam or water, was incorporated into all carriers, with the first being installed aboard {{USS|Franklin D. Roosevelt|CV-42|2}} during her 1968\u20131969 refit.<ref name=cox/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://ussfranklindroosevelt.com/?page_id=2264 |title=History |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=USS Franklin D. Roosevelt |accessdate=13 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151004200931/http://ussfranklindroosevelt.com/?page_id=2264 |archive-date=4 October 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Many other [[fire prevention|fire-safety]] improvements also stemmed from this incident.<ref name=cox/>\n\nDue to the first bomb blast, which killed nearly all of the trained [[damage controlman|firefighters]] on the ship, the remaining crew, who had no formal firefighting training, were forced to improvise.<ref>{{Cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=chuiyXQKw3I|title=USS Forrestal Mishap July 29, 1967|date=25 November 2006|access-date=26 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161110023541/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=chuiyXQKw3I|archive-date=10 November 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> All current Navy recruits receive week-long training in compartment identification, fixed and portable extinguishers, battle dress, self-contained breathing apparatus and emergency escape breathing devices. Recruits are tested on their knowledge and skills by having to use portable extinguishers and charged hoses to fight fires, as well as demonstrating the ability to egress from compartments that are heated and filled with smoke.<ref name=navylive/>\n\n=== Media ===\n\nThe disaster was a major news story and was featured under the headline \"Inferno at Sea\" on the cover of the 11 August 1967, issue of ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'' magazine.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/politics/azdc/2017/07/29/john-mccain-50-years-ago-uss-forrestal-tragedy/522101001/ |title=Sen. John McCain barely escaped death 50 years ago in the USS Forrestal disaster |last=Nowicki |first=Dan |date=28 July 2017 |work=[[The Arizona Republic]] |access-date=2018-07-27 |language=en |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe incident was featured on the first episode of [[the History Channel]]'s ''[[Shockwave (TV series)|Shockwave]]''<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.history.com/shows/shockwave/season-1/episode-1 |title=Watch Shockwave #1 Full Episode - Shockwave |website=HISTORY |language=en |access-date=2018-07-27 |df=dmy-all |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180727212150/https://www.history.com/shows/shockwave/season-1/episode-1 |archive-date=27 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and the third episode of the second season of the [[National Geographic (TV network)|National Geographic Channel]]'s ''[[Seconds From Disaster]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n''This article contains content in the public domain originally published by the U.S. government.''\n\n==External links==\n\n{{commons category|1967 USS Forrestal fire}}\n* US Navy [http://www.jag.navy.mil/library/investigations/USS%20FORRESTAL%20FIRE%2012%20AUG%2069%20PT%201.pdf Inves - Fire and explosions aboard USS Forrestal (CV 59) Part 1] [http://www.jag.navy.mil/library/investigations/USS%20FORRESTAL%20FIRE%2012%20AUG%2069%20PT%202.pdf Part 2] [http://www.jag.navy.mil/library/investigations/USS%20FORRESTAL%20FIRE%2012%20AUG%2069%20PT%203.pdf Part 3] (Official investigation) 19 Sep 1967 Judge Advocate General\n* US Navy. [http://www.navy.mil/navydata/navy_legacy_hr.asp?id=73 ''Forrestal'' fire]. from ''Naval Aviation News'', October 1967.\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090420103551/http://www.safetycenter.navy.mil/MEDIA/approach/theydidwhat/Forrestal.htm |date=20 April 2009 |title=Personal account of the USS ''Forrestal'' fire, July 29, 1967 }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160304185813/http://www.virtualwall.org/units/forrestal.htm Virtual Wall: A Memorial to the men who died in the ''Forrestal'' fire]\n* US Navy. [http://www.navy.mil/search/display.asp?story_id=2967 Witness to History: USS ''Forrestal'' Fire]. 1 August 2002.\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041105120949/https://wrc.navair-rdte.navy.mil/warfighter_enc/History/dyk/1stpage/forrfire.htm |date=5 November 2004 |title=Did You Know: The terrible fire aboard the USS ''Forrestal'' was the worst single Naval casualty event of the Viet Nam War? }}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.dcfp.navy.mil/mc/museum/FORRESTAL/Forrestal1.htm |title=US Navy Damage Control Museum: USS ''Forrestal'' |accessdate=7 February 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091006020626/http://www.dcfp.navy.mil/mc/museum/FORRESTAL/Forrestal1.htm |archivedate=6 October 2009}} \n* [http://www.navsource.org/archives/02/cv-59/59f-0729.htm NavSource.org: The ''Forrestal'' Fire, 29 July 1967, Ship's Logs]\n;Video\n* {{YouTube|chuiyXQKw3I|Video of USS ''Forrestal'' Mishap 29 July 1967}}\n* [https://archive.org/details/gov.ntis.ava19833vnb1 Trial by Fire: A Carrier Fights for Life] (US Navy Training film via Internet Archive)\n\n{{1967 shipwrecks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:USS Forrestal fire, 1967}}\n[[Category:Industrial fires and explosions in the United States]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1967]]\n[[Category:Non-combat naval accidents]]\n[[Category:Ship fires]]\n[[Category:Filmed accidental deaths|USS Forrestal fire, 1967]]\n[[Category:1967 fires|USS Forrestal fire, 1967]]\n[[Category:1967 disasters in the United States|USS Forrestal fire, 1967]]\n[[Category:1967 in Vietnam]]\n[[Category:July 1967 events]]\n[[Category:Explosions in 1967]]\n[[Category:Gulf of Tonkin]]\n[[Category:Maritime disasters]]\n[[Category:Aircraft carrier fires]]\n", "name_user": "Cobatfor", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBackground", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1967_USS_Forrestal_fire"}
{"title_page": "Doxofylline", "text_new": "{{Drugbox\n| verifiedrevid = 444222727\n| IUPAC_name = 7-(1,3-Dioxolan-2-ylmethyl)-1,3-dimethylpurine-2,6-dione\n| image = Doxofylline.svg\n| width = 175\n| image2 = Doxofylline-3D-balls.png\n| width2 = 225\n\n<!--Clinical data-->\n| tradename =\n| Drugs.com = {{drugs.com|international|doxofylline}}\n| pregnancy_category =\n| legal_status = Rx-only\n| routes_of_administration = [[Oral administration|By mouth]]\n\n<!--Pharmacokinetic data-->\n| bioavailability =\n| metabolism =\n| elimination_half-life =\n| excretion =\n\n<!--Identifiers-->\n| CAS_number_Ref = {{cascite|correct|??}}\n| CAS_number = 69975-86-6\n| ATC_prefix = R03\n| ATC_suffix = DA11\n| PubChem = 50942\n| UNII_Ref = {{fdacite|correct|FDA}}\n| UNII = MPM23GMO7Z\n| KEGG_Ref = {{keggcite|correct|kegg}}\n| KEGG = D03898\n| DrugBank = DB09273\n| ChemSpiderID = 46175\n\n<!--Chemical data-->\n| C=11 | H=14 | N=4 | O=4\n| molecular_weight = 266.25 g/mol\n| smiles = CN1C2=C(C(=O)N(C1=O)C)N(C=N2)CC3OCCO3\n| StdInChI = 1S/C11H14N4O4/c1-13-9-8(10(16)14(2)11(13)17)15(6-12-9)5-7-18-3-4-19-7/h6-7H,3-5H2,1-2H3\n| StdInChIKey = HWXIGFIVGWUZAO-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n}}\n\n'''Doxofylline''' (also known as '''doxophylline''') is a [[xanthine]] derivative [[drug]] used in the treatment of [[asthma]].<ref name=\"pmid3245738\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Cirillo R, Barone D, Franzone JS | title = Doxofylline, an antiasthmatic drug lacking affinity for adenosine receptors | journal = Archives Internationales de Pharmacodynamie et de Therapie | volume = 295 | issue =  | pages = 221\u201337 | year = 1988 | pmid = 3245738 | doi =  }}</ref>\n\n==Medical uses==\nIt has [[antitussive]]{{Citation needed|date=December 2008}} and [[bronchodilator]]<ref name=\"pmid2791671\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Poggi R, Brandolese R, Bernasconi M, Manzin E, Rossi A | title = Doxofylline and respiratory mechanics. Short-term effects in mechanically ventilated patients with airflow obstruction and respiratory failure | journal = Chest | volume = 96 | issue = 4 | pages = 772\u20138 | date = October 1989 | pmid = 2791671 | doi = 10.1378/chest.96.4.772 | url = http://www.chestjournal.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=2791671 | archive-url = https://archive.today/20130414124541/http://www.chestjournal.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=2791671 | url-status = dead | archive-date = 2013-04-14 }}</ref> effects, and acts as a [[phosphodiesterase inhibitor]].<ref name=\"pmid11268710\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Dini FL, Cogo R | title = Doxofylline: a new generation xanthine bronchodilator devoid of major cardiovascular adverse effects | journal = Current Medical Research and Opinion | volume = 16 | issue = 4 | pages = 258\u201368 | year = 2001 | pmid = 11268710 | doi = 10.1185/030079901750120196 }}</ref> Doxophylline is used to treat [[asthma]], [[Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease|COPD]] and [[bronchospasm]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Cazzola M, Calzetta L, Rogliani P, Page C, Matera MG | title = Impact of doxofylline in COPD: A pairwise meta-analysis | journal = Pulmonary Pharmacology & Therapeutics | volume = 51 | pages = 1\u20139 | date = August 2018 | pmid = 29705620 | doi = 10.1016/j.pupt.2018.04.010 | url = https://kclpure.kcl.ac.uk/portal/files/97650305/Impact_of_doxofylline_in_CAZZOLA_Accepted24April2018_GOLD_VOR_CC_BY_.pdf }}</ref>\n\nIn animal and human studies, it has shown similar efficacy to [[theophylline]] but with significantly fewer side effects.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Sankar J, Lodha R, Kabra SK | title = Doxofylline: The next generation methylxanthine | journal = Indian Journal of Pediatrics | volume = 75 | issue = 3 | pages = 251\u20134 | date = March 2008 | pmid = 18376093 | doi = 10.1007/s12098-008-0054-1 }}</ref> In February 2014, the US [[Food and Drug Administration|FDA]] granted an [[orphan drug]] designation to doxofylline for the treatment of [[bronchiectasis]] following the submission of an application by Alitair Pharmaceuticals, in May 2013.<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.hrsa.gov/sites/default/files/opa/programrequirements/orphandrugexclusion/janmar2015list.pdf |title=Orphan Drug Designations and Approvals List as of 12\u201001\u20102014 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.alitair.com/index.php/news-release-10-26-15|title=News Release 10/26/15| author = SMI Support |website=www.alitair.com|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://adisinsight.springer.com/drugs/800003876|title=Doxofylline - AdisInsight|website=adisinsight.springer.com|language=en|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref> further study required\n\n==Chemistry==\nUnlike other xanthines, doxofylline lacks any significant [[affinity (pharmacology)|affinity]] for [[adenosine receptor]]s and does not produce [[stimulant]] effects. This suggests that its antiasthmatic effects are mediated by another mechanism, perhaps its actions on [[phosphodiesterase]].<ref name=\"pmid3245738\" /> From a [[Pharmacokinetics|pharmacokinetic]] point of view, doxofylline importantly differs from theophylline also because it lacks the ability to interfere with the cytochrome enzymes [[CYP1A2]], [[CYP2E1]] and [[CYP3A4]], thus preventing significant interaction with other drugs metabolized via these pathways in the liver. <ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Mennini FS, Sciattella P, Marcellusi A, Marcobelli A, Russo A, Caputi AP | title = Treatment plan comparison in acute and chronic respiratory tract diseases: an observational study of doxophylline vs. theophylline | journal = Expert Review of Pharmacoeconomics & Outcomes Research | volume = 17 | issue = 5 | pages = 503\u2013510 | date = October 2017 | pmid = 28277853 | doi = 10.1080/14737167.2017.1301815 | url = http://eprints.kingston.ac.uk/38771/1/Mennini-F-S-38771-AAM.pdf }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Matera MG, Page C, Cazzola M | title = Doxofylline is not just another theophylline! | journal = International Journal of Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease | volume = 12 | pages = 3487\u20133493 | date = 2017-12-05 | pmid = 29255355 | pmc = 5723117 | doi = 10.2147/COPD.S150887 }}</ref>\n\n==Names==\nIt is marketed under many brand names worldwide, including: \nXiva, An Li Nuo Er, An Sai Ma, Ansimar, Asima, Bestofyline, Chuan Ning, D-Fyal, Dilatair, Doxiba, Doxobid, Doxobron, Doxofilina, Doxofillina, Doxofyllin, Doxoll, Doxophylline, Doxovent, Doxyjohn, Fei Te Ai Si, Jian Fang Neng, Lang Ming, Lv Meng, Mai Ping Xi, Maxivent, Mucosma, Na De Lai, Phylex, Phyllin, Puroxan, Rexipin, Shu Zhi, Shuai An, Shuweixin, Suo Di, Suo Ji, Suo Li An, Xi Si Nuo, Xin Qian Ping, Xin Xi Ping, Yi Suo, and Yili.<ref name=brands>{{cite web|title=Doxofylline - international brand names|url=https://www.drugs.com/international/doxofylline.html|publisher=Drugs.com|access-date=18 January 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIt is also marketed as a [[combination drug]] with [[terbutaline]] as Doxoll-TL, Mucosma-T  and Phylex-TR.<ref name=brands/>\n\nIt is also marketed as a combination drug with [[montelukast]] as  Doxoll-ML, Doxomont, Doxoril-M, Doxovent-M, Lunair-M, and Venidox-M.<ref name=brands/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Shukla D, Chakraborty S, Singh S, Mishra B | title = Doxofylline: a promising methylxanthine derivative for the treatment of asthma and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease | journal = Expert Opinion on Pharmacotherapy | volume = 10 | issue = 14 | pages = 2343\u201356 | date = October 2009 | pmid = 19678793 | doi = 10.1517/14656560903200667 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Asthma and copd rx}}\n{{Phosphodiesterase inhibitors}}\n\n[[Category:Dioxolanes]]\n[[Category:Phosphodiesterase inhibitors]]\n[[Category:Xanthines]]\n\n{{respiratory-system-drug-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Drugbox\n| verifiedrevid = 444222727\n| IUPAC_name = 7-(1,3-Dioxolan-2-ylmethyl)-1,3-dimethylpurine-2,6-dione\n| image = Doxofylline.svg\n| width = 175\n| image2 = Doxofylline-3D-balls.png\n| width2 = 225\n\n